{"title_page": "Nora Sourouzian", "text_new": "[[File:Nora Sourouzian 2019.jpg|alt=Portrait Picture Nora Sourouzian|thumb|Nora Sourouzian 2019]]\n'''Nora Sourouzian''' is a French-Canadian [[mezzo-soprano]] with Armenian roots.\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nBorn in Montr\u00e9al, she studied piano and voice at the [[University of McGill]] with Th\u00e9r\u00e8se Sevadjian]. During her time at McGill University she already sang Mrs Herring in ''[[Albert Herring]]'', the title roles in ''[[Giulio Cesare]]'' and ''[[Mignon]]'', the Komponist in ''[[Ariadne auf Naxos]]'', as well as H\u00e4nsel in ''[[Hansel and Gretel (opera)|H\u00e4nsel und Gretel]]'' with the [[Orchestre M\u00e9tropolitain de Montr\u00e9al]].\n\nFrom 1998 to 1999 she was a member of the Internationaal Opera Centrum Nederland in Amsterdam, where she sang Lucrezia in ''[[The Rape of Lucretia]]''.\n\n== Artistic career ==\nFrom 1999 to 2001, Sourouzian was part of the soloist ensemble of [[Staatstheater Kassel]].\n\nSince 2002 Sourouzian is a freelance opera singer. Her career, which leads her all over Europe, parts of USA, Canada, Chile, Asia and Mexico, consists of numerous leading roles both of well-known and rare repertoire. One of her key roles throughout many years has been [[Carmen]] which she interpreted in many opera houses such as [[Welsh National Opera]] (2004), [[Klagenfurt]], {{ill|Oper im Steinbruch St. Margarethen|de}} (2005), [[Op\u00e9ra de Qu\u00e9bec]], [[Den Norske Opera]] (2006), the [[Teatro Comunale Ponchielli]] in Cremona] (2008), [[Op\u00e9ra de Lausanne]] and Tokyo (2008\u20132009), [[Oper K\u00f6ln]] (2009), Leipzig and Bologna, [[Teatro Lirico di Cagliari]] (2010), Minnesota (2015).<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://mnopera.org/biography/nora-sourouzian/ |title = Nora Sourouzian|date = 2014-02-19}}</ref> and [[Palm Beach Opera]] (2016); She recently appeared in Santiago de Chile with Mahler's [[Symphony No. 3 (Mahler)|Symphony No. 3]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.uchile.cl/agenda/144002/concierto-de-la-orquesta-sinfonica-de-chile-sinfonia-n3-de-mahler|title=Concierto de la Orquesta Sinf\u00f3nica de Chile: Sinfon\u00eda n\u00b03 de Mahler - Universidad de Chile|website=www.uchile.cl|accessdate=Sep 22, 2019}}</ref> and sang Marguerite in ''[[La damnation de Faust]]'' at the [[Palacio de Bellas Artes]] Mexico.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.operaworld.es/berlioz-condena-a-fausto-al-infierno-por-amor-a-margarita-mefistofeles-triunfo-publico-complacido-en-bellas-artes/|title=Berlioz condena a Fausto al infierno por amor a Margarita. Mefist\u00f3feles triunf\u00f3. P\u00fablico complacido en Bellas Artes|date=2019-03-03}}</ref>\n\nSourouzian sang leading roles such as: Idamante (Mozart, ''[[Idomeneo]]''), Dorabella (Mozart, ''[[Cos\u00ec fan tutte]]''), Romeo (Bellini, ''[[I Capuleti e i Montecchi]]''), Marguerite (Berlioz, ''[[La damnation de Faust]]''),<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.wienerzeitung.at/nachrichten/kultur/buehne/140696-Faust-als-echter-Langeweiler.html |title = Faust als echter \"Langeweiler\" - Stadttheater Klagenfurt: \"Fausts Verdammnis\"}}</ref> Dulcin\u00e9e (Massenet's ''[[Don Quichotte]]'', production of Laurent Pelly in Palermo),<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.teatromassimo.it/sala-stampa/comunicati/don-quichotte-di-massenet-a-cento-anni-dal-debutto-in-un-nuovo-allestimento.html |title = Don Quichotte di Massenet a cento anni dal debutto in un nuovo allestimento firmato da Laurent Pelly prodotto dal Teatro Massimo &#124; Comunicati - Teatro Massimo Palermo}}</ref> Laura (A. Ponchielli, ''[[La Gioconda (opera)|La Gioconda]]'')<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.oper-aktuell.info/kritiken/artikel/st-gallen-la-gioconda-01-02-2014.html | title=Details}}</ref> and La Favorita (Donizetti, ''[[La favorite]]''),<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.operabase.com/ref/1878/63811/de |title = Reference - Operabase}}</ref> Eboli (Verdi, ''[[Don Carlo]]'')<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://onlinemerker.com/gars-burgfestspiele-don-carlo-verdi-und-der-herr-der-ringe-als-packendes-opernspektakel-premiere/ |title = GARS/ Burgfestspiele: DON CARLO. \"Verdi und der \"Herr der Ringe\" als packendes Opernspektakel. Premiere|date = 2015-07-18}}</ref> and Azucena] (Verdi, ''[[Il trovatore]]'').<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://bachtrack.com/de_DE/kritik-il-trovatore-baur-sourouzian-sanguineti-pgossov-kos-oper-graz-september-2017 | title=Triumph f\u00fcr Azucena in der Grazer Neuproduktion von Il trovatore}}</ref> Her role debut and strong interpretation of the role at [[Graz Opera]] in 2017 was highly acclaimed in the press., <ref>[[Opernglas]], Auff\u00fchrungen, November 2017, page 16-17.</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.oper-graz.com/production-details/it |title = Il Trovatore &#124; Oper Graz}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.deropernfreund.de/graz-12.html | title=Graz}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.kleinezeitung.at/kultur/klassik/5294882/KritikOper-Graz_Verdis-Troubadour-im-Variete | title=Kritik/Oper Graz: Verdis \"Troubadour\" im Variet\u00e9| date=2017-10-05}}</ref>,.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.meinbezirk.at/graz/c-leute/perfekte-premiere-von-giuseppe-verdis-il-trovatore_a2268238 |title = Perfekte Premiere von Giuseppe Verdi\u00b4s \"Il Trovatore\"}}</ref> In January 2019 she appeared at [[Seattle Opera]] also in the role of Azucena.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.operawarhorses.com/2019/01/15/review-il-trovatore-impressive-seattle-opera-debuts-for-meade-muehle-mayes-and-sourouzian-january-13-2019/ |title = Review, \"Il Trovatore\": Impressive Seattle Opera debuts for Meade, Muehle, Mayes and Sourouzian \u2013 January 13, 2019|date = 2019-01-16}}</ref>\n\nAlongside well-known repertoire, Sourouzian regularly sings opera roles of rare pieces. She sang Alo\u00e8s<ref>[[Opernglas]], Z\u00dcRICH, L'Etoile, Januar 2007</ref> in [[David Pountney]]'s production of Chabrier's ''[[L'\u00e9toile (opera)|L'\u00e9toile]]'' under [[John Eliot Gardiner]] at [[Z\u00fcrich Opera House]] in 2006,<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.impresario.ch/review/revchaeto.htm | title=Kritiken: Chabrier / l'\u00c9toile}}</ref> Maria Callas in Michael Daugherty's opera ''[[Jackie O (opera)|Jackie O]]'' in a production of [[Damiano Michieletto]], which is available on DVD.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.discogs.com/de/Michael-Daugherty-Jackie-O/release/2896077 | title=Michael Daugherty - Jackie O}}</ref> Further she sang the role of Zul\u00e9ma in [[Th\u00e9odore Dubois]]' ''Aben-Hamet'' under [[Jean-Claude Malgoire]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.anaclase.com/content/th%C3%A9odore-dubois-0|title=Th\u00e9odore Dubois &#124; Anaclase|website=www.anaclase.com|accessdate=Sep 22, 2019}}</ref> Herodias in [[Antoine Mariotte]]'s opera ''[[Salom\u00e9 (Mariotte)|Salom\u00e9]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/new-music/11170707/Nora-Sourouzian-new-music.html|title=Nora Sourouzian \u2013 New Music|author=Rupert Christiansen|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=18 October 2014|access-date=12 August 2019|author-link=Rupert Christiansen}}</ref> the role of Florinda in the newly written opera ''O Rapaz de Bronze'' by {{ill|Nuno C\u00f4rte-Real|pt}},<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rtp.pt/noticias/cultura/opera-o-rapaz-de-bronze-em-estreia-mundial-na-casa-da-musica_n162497|title=Opera \"O Rapaz de Bronze\" em estreia mundial na Casa da Musica|last=|first=|date=|website=R\u00e1dio e Televis\u00e3o de Portugal|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> as well as the role of Marfa in Dvo\u0159\u00e1ks opera ''[[Dimitrij (opera)|Dimitrij]]'' at [[Bard SummerScape]], New York, in summer 2017.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://operawire.com/bard-summerscape-2017-festival-dimitrij-a-flawed-production-makes-compelling-case-for-dvoraks-rarely-heard-sixth-opera/ | title=Bard SummerScape Festival 2017 Review \u2013 Dimitrij: A Flawed Production Makes Compelling Case for Dvo\u0159\u00e1k's Rarely Heard Sixth Opera \u2013 Opera Wire}}</ref> Her interpretation of Th\u00e9r\u00e8se (Massenet, ''[[Th\u00e9r\u00e8se (opera)|Th\u00e9r\u00e8se]]'') and Anita (Massenet, ''[[La Navarraise]]'') at the [[Wexford Festival]] 2013 was highly praised in the international press.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/opera/10418174/ThereseLa-Navarraise-Wexford-Festival.html|title=Massenet's ''Th\u00e9r\u00e8se''/''La Navarraise'', Wexford Festival Opera, review|author=Rupert Christiansen|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=31 October 2013|access-date=12 August 2019|author-link=Rupert Christiansen}}</ref>\n\nSourouzian collaborates with directors such as [[Calixto Bieito]] (''Cos\u00ec fan tutte''), [[Robert Carsen]] (''Carmen''), [[Moshe Leiser and Patrice Caurier]] (''Carmen''), [[Christine Mielitz]] (''Cos\u00ec fan tutte''), [[Christof Loy]] (''Carmen''), [[David Pountney]] (''L\u2019\u00c9toile''), Barbe & Doucet (''P\u00e9n\u00e9lope'', ''Th\u00e9r\u00e8se'' and ''La Navarraise'') and [[Vera Nemirova]] ([[Rusalka (opera)|Rusalka]] at [[Theater St. Gallen]] 2019).<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.theatersg.ch/de/kuenstler/nora-sourouzian/682 | title=Theater St.Gallen}}</ref>\n\nShe has so far sung under the baton of conductors like [[Christoph Eschenbach]], [[Marc Minkowski]], [[Ed Spanjaard]], [[Franz Welser-M\u00f6st]], [[Hubert Soudant]], {{ill|Dietfried Bernet|de}}, [[Cyril Diederich]], [[Joseph Rescigno]] and [[Nicholas McGegan]].\n\n== Competitions ==\n* First prize at Prix d'Expression Musicale \u2013 1995\n* Winner at Fondation Charles Emiles Gadbois\n* First prize at Concours de la Journ\u00e9e de la Musique Fran\u00e7aise \u2013 Montr\u00e9al 1997\n* Second prize at D\u00e9but-CBC \u2013 USA 1997\n* First prize at NATS International \u2013 1997\n* First prize in all categories at Concours de Musique du Canada 1997\n* First prize at Jeunes Ambassadeurs Lyriques 1999<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.scena.org/lsm/sm17-2/sm17-2_TL20_FR.html|title=Le Th\u00e9\u00e2tre Lyrichor\u00e9gra 20 a 35 ans (1976-2011)|website=www.scena.org|accessdate=Sep 22, 2019}}</ref>\n* Finalist at Hans Gabor Belvedere \u2013 Vienna 1999\n* Finalist at the 3rd Wagnerstimmen Wettbewerb Saarbr\u00fccken in 2000<ref>http://www.rwv-saarland.de/files/pdfs/RWV_Saarland_1956-2006.pdf</ref>\n\n== Recordings ==\n*[https://www.discogs.com/Michael-Daugherty-Jackie-O/release/2896077 ''Jackie O'', Michael Daugherty]\n*[https://www.amazon.de/STRAUSS-Salome-Teatro-Comunale-Bologna/dp/B00IKXQTOK ''Salome'', R. Strauss]\n*[https://www.europadisc.co.uk/classical/109529/Opera_de_Montreal:_Le_Gala_du_30th_Anniversaire.htm ''Atma Classic Gala 30th Anniversaire Montrea''l]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official|http://www.norasourouzian.com/}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Opera}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{draft categories|\n\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sourouzian, Nora}}\n[[Category:Canadian mezzo-sopranos]]\n[[Category:Operatic mezzo-sopranos]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Armenian descent]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian singers]]\n[[Category:McGill University alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century women singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century women singers]]\n[[Category:Singers from Montreal]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Nora Sourouzian 2019.jpg|alt=Portrait Picture Nora Sourouzian|thumb|Nora Sourouzian 2019]]\n'''Nora Sourouzian''' is a French-Canadian [[mezzo-soprano]] with Armenian roots.\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nBorn in Montr\u00e9al, she studied piano and voice at the [[University of McGill]] with Th\u00e9r\u00e8se Sevadjian]. During her time at McGill University she already sang Mrs Herring in ''[[Albert Herring]]'', the title roles in ''[[Giulio Cesare]]'' and ''[[Mignon]]'', the Komponist in ''[[Ariadne auf Naxos]]'', as well as H\u00e4nsel in ''[[Hansel and Gretel (opera)|H\u00e4nsel und Gretel]]'' with the [[Orchestre M\u00e9tropolitain de Montr\u00e9al]].\n\nFrom 1998 to 1999 she was a member of the Internationaal Opera Centrum Nederland in Amsterdam, where she sang Lucrezia in ''[[The Rape of Lucretia]]''.\n\n== Artistic career ==\nFrom 1999 to 2001, Sourouzian was part of the soloist ensemble of [[Staatstheater Kassel]].\n\nSince 2002 Sourouzian is a freelance opera singer. Her career, which leads her all over Europe, parts of USA, Canada, Chile, Asia and Mexico, consists of numerous leading roles both of well-known and rare repertoire. One of her key roles throughout many years has been [[Carmen]] which she interpreted in many opera houses such as [[Welsh National Opera]] (2004), [[Klagenfurt]], {{ill|Oper im Steinbruch St. Margarethen|de}} (2005), [[Op\u00e9ra de Qu\u00e9bec]], [[Den Norske Opera]] (2006), the [[Teatro Comunale Ponchielli]] in Cremona] (2008), [[Op\u00e9ra de Lausanne]] and Tokyo (2008\u20132009), [[Oper K\u00f6ln]] (2009), Leipzig and Bologna, [[Teatro Lirico di Cagliari]] (2010), Minnesota (2015).<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://mnopera.org/biography/nora-sourouzian/ |title = Nora Sourouzian|date = 2014-02-19}}</ref> and [[Palm Beach Opera]] (2016); She recently appeared in Santiago de Chile with Mahler's [[Symphony No. 3 (Mahler)|Symphony No. 3]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.uchile.cl/agenda/144002/concierto-de-la-orquesta-sinfonica-de-chile-sinfonia-n3-de-mahler|title=Concierto de la Orquesta Sinf\u00f3nica de Chile: Sinfon\u00eda n\u00b03 de Mahler - Universidad de Chile|website=www.uchile.cl|accessdate=Sep 22, 2019}}</ref> and sang Marguerite in ''[[La damnation de Faust]]'' at the [[Palacio de Bellas Artes]] Mexico.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.operaworld.es/berlioz-condena-a-fausto-al-infierno-por-amor-a-margarita-mefistofeles-triunfo-publico-complacido-en-bellas-artes/|title=Berlioz condena a Fausto al infierno por amor a Margarita. Mefist\u00f3feles triunf\u00f3. P\u00fablico complacido en Bellas Artes|date=2019-03-03}}</ref>\n\nSourouzian sang leading roles such as: Idamante (Mozart, ''[[Idomeneo]]''), Dorabella (Mozart, ''[[Cos\u00ec fan tutte]]''), Romeo (Bellini, ''[[I Capuleti e i Montecchi]]''), Marguerite (Berlioz, ''[[La damnation de Faust]]''),<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.wienerzeitung.at/nachrichten/kultur/buehne/140696-Faust-als-echter-Langeweiler.html |title = Faust als echter \"Langeweiler\" - Stadttheater Klagenfurt: \"Fausts Verdammnis\"}}</ref> Dulcin\u00e9e (Massenet's ''[[Don Quichotte]]'', production of Laurent Pelly in Palermo),<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.teatromassimo.it/sala-stampa/comunicati/don-quichotte-di-massenet-a-cento-anni-dal-debutto-in-un-nuovo-allestimento.html |title = Don Quichotte di Massenet a cento anni dal debutto in un nuovo allestimento firmato da Laurent Pelly prodotto dal Teatro Massimo &#124; Comunicati - Teatro Massimo Palermo}}</ref> Laura (A. Ponchielli, ''[[La Gioconda (opera)|La Gioconda]]'')<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.oper-aktuell.info/kritiken/artikel/st-gallen-la-gioconda-01-02-2014.html | title=Details}}</ref> and La Favorita (Donizetti, ''[[La favorite]]''),<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.operabase.com/ref/1878/63811/de |title = Reference - Operabase}}</ref> Eboli (Verdi, ''[[Don Carlo]]'')<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://onlinemerker.com/gars-burgfestspiele-don-carlo-verdi-und-der-herr-der-ringe-als-packendes-opernspektakel-premiere/ |title = GARS/ Burgfestspiele: DON CARLO. \"Verdi und der \"Herr der Ringe\" als packendes Opernspektakel. Premiere|date = 2015-07-18}}</ref> and Azucena] (Verdi, ''[[Il trovatore]]'').<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://bachtrack.com/de_DE/kritik-il-trovatore-baur-sourouzian-sanguineti-pgossov-kos-oper-graz-september-2017 | title=Triumph f\u00fcr Azucena in der Grazer Neuproduktion von Il trovatore}}</ref> Her role debut and strong interpretation of the role at [[Graz Opera]] in 2017 was highly acclaimed in the press.,,<ref>[[Opernglas]], Auff\u00fchrungen, November 2017, page 16-17.</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.oper-graz.com/production-details/it |title = Il Trovatore &#124; Oper Graz}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.deropernfreund.de/graz-12.html | title=Graz}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.kleinezeitung.at/kultur/klassik/5294882/KritikOper-Graz_Verdis-Troubadour-im-Variete | title=Kritik/Oper Graz: Verdis \"Troubadour\" im Variet\u00e9| date=2017-10-05}}</ref>,.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.meinbezirk.at/graz/c-leute/perfekte-premiere-von-giuseppe-verdis-il-trovatore_a2268238 |title = Perfekte Premiere von Giuseppe Verdi\u00b4s \"Il Trovatore\"}}</ref> In January 2019 she appeared at [[Seattle Opera]] also in the role of Azucena.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.operawarhorses.com/2019/01/15/review-il-trovatore-impressive-seattle-opera-debuts-for-meade-muehle-mayes-and-sourouzian-january-13-2019/ |title = Review, \"Il Trovatore\": Impressive Seattle Opera debuts for Meade, Muehle, Mayes and Sourouzian \u2013 January 13, 2019|date = 2019-01-16}}</ref>\n\nAlongside well-known repertoire, Sourouzian regularly sings opera roles of rare pieces. She sang Alo\u00e8s<ref>[[Opernglas]], Z\u00dcRICH, L'Etoile, Januar 2007</ref> in [[David Pountney]]'s production of Chabrier's ''[[L'\u00e9toile (opera)|L'\u00e9toile]]'' under [[John Eliot Gardiner]] at [[Z\u00fcrich Opera House]] in 2006,<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.impresario.ch/review/revchaeto.htm | title=Kritiken: Chabrier / l'\u00c9toile}}</ref> Maria Callas in Michael Daugherty's opera ''[[Jackie O (opera)|Jackie O]]'' in a production of [[Damiano Michieletto]], which is available on DVD.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.discogs.com/de/Michael-Daugherty-Jackie-O/release/2896077 | title=Michael Daugherty - Jackie O}}</ref> Further she sang the role of Zul\u00e9ma in [[Th\u00e9odore Dubois]]' ''Aben-Hamet'' under [[Jean-Claude Malgoire]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.anaclase.com/content/th%C3%A9odore-dubois-0|title=Th\u00e9odore Dubois &#124; Anaclase|website=www.anaclase.com|accessdate=Sep 22, 2019}}</ref> Herodias in [[Antoine Mariotte]]'s opera ''[[Salom\u00e9 (Mariotte)|Salom\u00e9]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/new-music/11170707/Nora-Sourouzian-new-music.html|title=Nora Sourouzian \u2013 New Music|author=Rupert Christiansen|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=18 October 2014|access-date=12 August 2019|author-link=Rupert Christiansen}}</ref> the role of Florinda in the newly written opera ''O Rapaz de Bronze'' by {{ill|Nuno C\u00f4rte-Real|pt}},<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rtp.pt/noticias/cultura/opera-o-rapaz-de-bronze-em-estreia-mundial-na-casa-da-musica_n162497|title=Opera \"O Rapaz de Bronze\" em estreia mundial na Casa da Musica|last=|first=|date=|website=R\u00e1dio e Televis\u00e3o de Portugal|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> as well as the role of Marfa in Dvo\u0159\u00e1ks opera ''[[Dimitrij (opera)|Dimitrij]]'' at [[Bard SummerScape]], New York, in summer 2017.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://operawire.com/bard-summerscape-2017-festival-dimitrij-a-flawed-production-makes-compelling-case-for-dvoraks-rarely-heard-sixth-opera/ | title=Bard SummerScape Festival 2017 Review \u2013 Dimitrij: A Flawed Production Makes Compelling Case for Dvo\u0159\u00e1k's Rarely Heard Sixth Opera \u2013 Opera Wire}}</ref> Her interpretation of Th\u00e9r\u00e8se (Massenet, ''[[Th\u00e9r\u00e8se (opera)|Th\u00e9r\u00e8se]]'') and Anita (Massenet, ''[[La Navarraise]]'') at the [[Wexford Festival]] 2013 was highly praised in the international press.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/opera/10418174/ThereseLa-Navarraise-Wexford-Festival.html|title=Massenet's ''Th\u00e9r\u00e8se''/''La Navarraise'', Wexford Festival Opera, review|author=Rupert Christiansen|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=31 October 2013|access-date=12 August 2019|author-link=Rupert Christiansen}}</ref>\n\nSourouzian collaborates with directors such as [[Calixto Bieito]] (''Cos\u00ec fan tutte''), [[Robert Carsen]] (''Carmen''), [[Moshe Leiser and Patrice Caurier]] (''Carmen''), [[Christine Mielitz]] (''Cos\u00ec fan tutte''), [[Christof Loy]] (''Carmen''), [[David Pountney]] (''L\u2019\u00c9toile''), Barbe & Doucet (''P\u00e9n\u00e9lope'', ''Th\u00e9r\u00e8se'' and ''La Navarraise'') and [[Vera Nemirova]] ([[Rusalka (opera)|Rusalka]] at [[Theater St. Gallen]] 2019).<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.theatersg.ch/de/kuenstler/nora-sourouzian/682 | title=Theater St.Gallen}}</ref>\n\nShe has so far sung under the baton of conductors like [[Christoph Eschenbach]], [[Marc Minkowski]], [[Ed Spanjaard]], [[Franz Welser-M\u00f6st]], [[Hubert Soudant]], {{ill|Dietfried Bernet|de}}, [[Cyril Diederich]], [[Joseph Rescigno]] and [[Nicholas McGegan]].\n\n== Competitions ==\n* First Price at Prix d'Expression Musicale \u2013 1995\n* Winner at Fondation Charles Emiles Gadbois\n* First Price at Concours de la Journ\u00e9e de la Musique Fran\u00e7aise \u2013 Montr\u00e9al 1997\n* Second Price at D\u00e9but-CBC \u2013 USA 1997\n* First Price at NATS International \u2013 1997\n* First Price in all categories at Concours de Musique du Canada 1997\n* First Price at Jeunes Ambassadeurs Lyriques 1999<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.scena.org/lsm/sm17-2/sm17-2_TL20_FR.html|title=Le Th\u00e9\u00e2tre Lyrichor\u00e9gra 20 a 35 ans (1976-2011)|website=www.scena.org|accessdate=Sep 22, 2019}}</ref>\n* Finalist at Hans Gabor Belvedere \u2013 Vienna 1999\n* Finalist at the 3rd Wagnerstimmen Wettbewerb Saarbr\u00fccken in 2000<ref>http://www.rwv-saarland.de/files/pdfs/RWV_Saarland_1956-2006.pdf</ref>\n\n== Recordings ==\n*[https://www.discogs.com/Michael-Daugherty-Jackie-O/release/2896077 ''Jackie O'', Michael Daugherty]\n*[https://www.amazon.de/STRAUSS-Salome-Teatro-Comunale-Bologna/dp/B00IKXQTOK ''Salome'', R. Strauss]\n*[https://www.europadisc.co.uk/classical/109529/Opera_de_Montreal:_Le_Gala_du_30th_Anniversaire.htm ''Atma Classic Gala 30th Anniversaire Montrea''l]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official|http://www.norasourouzian.com/}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Opera}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{draft categories|\n\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sourouzian, Nora}}\n[[Category:Canadian mezzo-sopranos]]\n[[Category:Operatic mezzo-sopranos]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Armenian descent]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian singers]]\n[[Category:McGill University alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century women singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century women singers]]\n[[Category:Singers from Montreal]]\n", "name_user": "WereSpielChequers", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo fixing, replaced: Second Price \u2192 Second prize, First Price \u2192 First prize (5),typo(s) fixed: ,, \u2192 ,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nora_Sourouzian"}
{"title_page": "Something in the Air", "text_new": "{{About|the song by Thunderclap Newman}}\n{{Refimprove|date=March 2014}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Something in the Air\n| cover      = ThunderclapNewman-SomethingintheAir.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Thunderclap Newman]]\n| album      = [[Hollywood Dream]]\n| B-side     = \"Wilhelmina\"\n| released   = {{start date|1969|05}}\n| format     = [[7-inch single]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = \n| length     = {{Duration|m=3|s=53}}\n| label      = [[Track Records|Track]]\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Speedy Keen]]}}\n| producer   = [[Pete Townshend]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = Accidents\n| next_year  = 1970\n}}\n\n\"'''Something in the Air'''\" is a song recorded by [[Thunderclap Newman]], written by [[Speedy Keen]] who also sang the song. It was a No. 1 single for three weeks in the [[UK Singles Chart]] in July 1969.<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book\n| first= David\n| last= Roberts\n| year= 2006\n| title= [[British Hit Singles & Albums]]\n| edition= 19th\n| publisher= Guinness World Records Limited \n| location= London\n| isbn= 1-904994-10-5\n| page= 234}}</ref> The song has been used for films, television and adverts, and has been covered by several artists. The track was also included on [[Thunderclap Newman]]'s only album release ''[[Hollywood Dream]]'' over a year later.\n\n==Background==\nIn 1969, [[Pete Townshend]], [[The Who]]'s [[guitarist]], was the catalyst behind the formation of the band. The concept was to create a band to perform songs written by [[drummer]] and singer [[Speedy Keen]], who had written \"[[Armenia City in the Sky]]\", the first track on ''[[The Who Sell Out]]''.<ref>John Dougan, {{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/whosellout00doug |url-access=registration |title=The Who sell out|page=[https://archive.org/details/whosellout00doug/page/98 98] |publisher=Continuum International Publishing Group |year=2006|isbn=0826417434|accessdate=2009-11-20 }}</ref> Townshend recruited jazz pianist Andy \"Thunderclap\" Newman (a friend from art college),<ref>Kim Cooper, David Smay, {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=o4wRvuoA0QYC&pg=PA165 |title=Lost in the grooves|page=165 |publisher=Routledge |date=2005 |isbn=0415969980 |accessdate=2009-11-20 }}</ref> and 15-year-old [[Glasgow|Glaswegian]] guitarist [[Jimmy McCulloch]], who subsequently played lead guitar in [[Paul McCartney]]'s [[Wings (band)|Wings]] from 1974 to 1977 and died of a heroin overdose in 1979 aged 26.<ref>Jeremy Simmonds, {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bMBf3TYZigQC&pg=PT143 |title=The Encyclopedia of Dead Rock Stars |page=124 |publisher=Chicago Review Press |date=2008 |isbn=1556527543|accessdate=2009-11-20 }}</ref> Keen played the drums and sang the lead.\n\n==Production==\nTownshend produced the single,<ref>Dave Spencer, {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MXkF1c8uRsoC&pg=PA97 |title=A Smudge on My Lens, page 97 |publisher=Troubador Publishing Ltd |year=2008 |isbn=1906510784 |accessdate=23 February 2019}}</ref> arranged the strings, and played bass under the pseudonym Bijou Drains.<ref>{{cite interview |last=Townshend |first=Pete |subjectlink=Pete Townshend |interviewer=[[Liz Kershaw]] |title=Liz Kershaw, BBC 6music |publisher=BBC Radio|date=November 16, 2019 }}</ref> Originally titled \"Revolution\" but later renamed to avoid confusion with [[the Beatles]]' 1968 [[Revolution (Beatles song)|song of the same name]], \"Something in the Air\" captured post-[[flower power]] rebellion, marrying McCulloch's sweeping acoustic and glowing electric guitars, Keen's powerful drumming and yearning falsetto, and Newman's felicitous piano solo.\n\nThe song, beginning in [[E major]], has three key changes, its second verse climbing to [[F-sharp major]], and, via a roundabout transition, goes down to [[C major]] for Newman's barrelhouse piano solo. Following this, the last verse is, like the second, a tone above the previous verse, closing the song in [[A-flat major]].\n\n==Reception==\nThe single reached No. 1 in the UK Singles Chart just three weeks after release, holding off [[Elvis Presley]] in the process. The scale of the song's success surprised everyone and there were no plans to promote Thunderclap Newman with live performances. Eventually a line-up - augmented by  Jim Pitman-Avory on bass and McCulloch's elder brother Jack on drums - played a handful of gigs. Personal records say the band played live only five times, although Keen referred to a two-month tour, playing \"everywhere\". In the UK, a follow-up single, \"Accidents\", came out only in May 1970 and charted at No. 46 for a week. An album, ''Hollywood Dream'', peaked in ''[[Billboard magazine|Billboard]]'' at No. 163. Thus, the song and the band were forever linked as a [[one hit wonder]]. [[Labelle]] recorded an emotional cover of it alongside \"[[The Revolution Will Not Be Televised]]\" by [[Gil Scott-Heron]] for their 1973 album, ''[[Pressure Cookin']]''.\n\n==Personnel==\n*[[Speedy Keen]] - [[double tracking|double-tracked]] lead vocal, drums\n*[[Jimmy McCulloch]] - lead and rhythm guitars\n*[[Pete Townshend]] - bass guitar (credited to \"Bijou Drains\"), orchestral arrangement\n*Andy \"Thunderclap\" Newman - piano, lead vocals on \"Wilhelmina\"\n\n==Chart performance (Thunderclap Newman version)==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1969)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Germany|13|artist=Thunderclap Newman|song=Something in the Air }}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|9|artist=Thunderclap Newman|song=Something in the Air }}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UKsinglesbyname|1|artist=Thunderclap Newman|song=Something in the Air}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardhot100|37|artist=Thunderclap Newman|song=Something in the Air }}\n|}\n\n==Appearance in other media==\n\"Something in the Air\" by Thunderclap Newman appeared on the soundtracks of several films, such as ''[[The Magic Christian (film)|The Magic Christian]]'' (1969), which helped the single reach No. 37 in the United States, and ''[[The Strawberry Statement (film)|The Strawberry Statement]]'' (1970), which prompted a reissue of the single that \"bubbled under\" the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 at No. 120. It later appeared in ''[[Kingpin (1996 film)|Kingpin]]'' (1996), ''[[Almost Famous]]'' (2000), ''[[The Dish]]'' (2000), and ''[[The Girl Next Door (2004 film)|The Girl Next Door]]'' (2004). It also appeared on and was the title of the second disc in the Deluxe Edition of the ''[[Easy Rider (soundtrack)|Easy Rider]]'' soundtrack.\n\n\"Something in the Air\" has been used extensively in television, most notably on an advertisement for [[British Airways]] which featured [[PJ O'Rourke]]. The song also appeared in a [[retro]] [[Television advertisement|TV advert]] for the [[Austin Mini]] in the early 1990s, featuring 1960s fashion model ''[[Twiggy]]''. More recently, a version of the song was used in the advertisements for the mobile phone service provider [[TalkTalk Group|TalkTalk]]. (A similar advert for TalkTalk shown at the beginning of advert breaks during ''[[Big Brother (UK)|Big Brother]]'' features the opening bars). The song was featured in a number of episodes of 1960s-set UK police series ''[[Heartbeat (UK TV series)|Heartbeat]]''. It is also used as the 'on hold' music for The Carphone Warehouse, of which Talk Talk is a part. The song was also featured in the pilot episode of the American television show ''[[Aliens in America]]'' and in the third-season episode ''[[Creative Writing (My Name Is Earl)|Bad Earl]]'' of ''[[My Name Is Earl]]''.  A version of the song recorded by [[Ocean Colour Scene]] was previously used by telephone provider [[Ionica (company)|Ionica]]. In 2008, this song appeared in a [[Coca-Cola]] commercial in [[Taiwan]]. It was also recently used in an episode of ''[[Prime Suspect 1973]]''.\n\n==Musical quotation==\n\"Something in the Air\" features a short burst of ''[[La Marseillaise]]'' - the national anthem of France. The ''revolution'' reference in the song's lyrics has subtly been hinted at in the synthesised brass arrangement from 3'30\". ''La Marseillaise'' also features in the ''[[1812 Overture]]'' by [[Pyotr Ilyich Tchaikovsky]] and in the opening of the [[Beatles]]' 1967 single [[All You Need Is Love]].\n\n==Covers==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Something in the Air\n| cover      = Something in the air tom petty.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Tom Petty and the Heartbreakers]]\n| album      = [[Greatest Hits (Tom Petty album)|Greatest Hits]]\n| released   = January 31, 1994\n| format     =\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      =\n| length     = 3:17\n| label      = [[MCA Inc.|MCA]]\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Speedy Keen]]}}\n| producer   = [[Rick Rubin]]\n| prev_title = [[Mary Jane's Last Dance]]\n| prev_year  = 1993\n| next_title = [[You Don't Know How It Feels]]\n| next_year  = 1994\n}}\nThe song has been covered by a number of artists, including:\n* The [[Mandrake Memorial]] in 1969\n* [[Labelle]] in 1973\n* [[Herbie Mann]] in 1974\n* [[Simon Park]] in 1974\n* [[Gamma (band)|Gamma]] in 1980\n* [[Eurythmics]] in 1985\n* [[Fish (singer)|Fish]] in 1991\n* [[The Lightning Seeds]] and [[Trip Shakespeare]] in 1992\n* [[Tom Petty and the Heartbreakers]] in 1994\n* [[U.K. Subs]] in 2000\n* [[The Superjesus]] in 2001\n* [[Elbow (band)|Elbow]] and [[Wellwater Conspiracy]] in 2003\n* [[Wilco]] live in late 2004 and throughout 2005 \n* [[Hayley Sanderson]] in 2006{{Citation needed|date=November 2009}}\n* [[Donald Fagen]] with the [[Dukes of September]]\n* [[Polyphonic Spree]] live since 2010\n* New Zealand/Australian band [[Dragon (band)|Dragon]] covered the song on their album, ''[[It's All Too Beautiful (album)|It's All Too Beautiful]]'' (2011). \n* [[Dixie Chicks]] live on select final dates of the [[DCX MMXVI World Tour]] in 2017.\n* [[Luna (1990s American band)|Luna]] on their 2019 album ''Postscripts''. Lead guitarist Sean Eden on vocals. \n\n===Tom Petty's version===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1994)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Canadian ''RPM'' Top Singles\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|26\n|-\n|UK Singles Chart\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|53\n|-\n|U.S. ''Billboard'' [[Hot Mainstream Rock Tracks|Album Rock Tracks]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|19\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1969 singles]]\n[[Category:Debut singles]]\n[[Category:UK Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Labelle songs]]\n[[Category:Protest songs]]\n[[Category:Thunderclap Newman songs]]\n[[Category:Tom Petty songs]]\n[[Category:Track Records singles]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Pete Townshend]]\n[[Category:1969 songs]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the song by Thunderclap Newman}}\n{{Refimprove|date=March 2014}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Something in the Air\n| cover      = ThunderclapNewman-SomethingintheAir.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Thunderclap Newman]]\n| album      = [[Hollywood Dream]]\n| B-side     = \"Wilhelmina\"\n| released   = {{start date|1969|05}}\n| format     = [[7-inch single]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = \n| length     = {{Duration|m=3|s=53}}\n| label      = [[Track Records|Track]]\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Speedy Keen]]}}\n| producer   = [[Pete Townshend]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = Accidents\n| next_year  = 1970\n}}\n\n\"'''Something in the Air'''\" is a song recorded by [[Thunderclap Newman]], written by [[Speedy Keen]] who also sang the song. It was a No. 1 single for three weeks in the [[UK Singles Chart]] in July 1969.<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book\n| first= David\n| last= Roberts\n| year= 2006\n| title= [[British Hit Singles & Albums]]\n| edition= 19th\n| publisher= Guinness World Records Limited \n| location= London\n| isbn= 1-904994-10-5\n| page= 234}}</ref> The song has been used for films, television and adverts, and has been covered by several artists. The track was also included on [[Thunderclap Newman]]'s only album release ''[[Hollywood Dream]]'' over a year later.\n\n==Background==\nIn 1969, [[Pete Townshend]], [[The Who]]'s [[guitarist]], was the catalyst behind the formation of the band. The concept was to create a band to perform songs written by [[drummer]] and singer [[Speedy Keen]], who had written \"[[Armenia City in the Sky]]\", the first track on ''[[The Who Sell Out]]''.<ref>John Dougan, {{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/whosellout00doug |url-access=registration |title=The Who sell out|page=[https://archive.org/details/whosellout00doug/page/98 98] |publisher=Continuum International Publishing Group |year=2006|isbn=0826417434|accessdate=2009-11-20 }}</ref> Townshend recruited jazz pianist Andy \"Thunderclap\" Newman (a friend from art college),<ref>Kim Cooper, David Smay, {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=o4wRvuoA0QYC&pg=PA165 |title=Lost in the grooves|page=165 |publisher=Routledge |date=2005 |isbn=0415969980 |accessdate=2009-11-20 }}</ref> and 15-year-old [[Glasgow|Glaswegian]] guitarist [[Jimmy McCulloch]], who subsequently played lead guitar in [[Paul McCartney]]'s [[Wings (band)|Wings]] from 1974 to 1977 and died of a heroin overdose in 1979 aged 26.<ref>Jeremy Simmonds, {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bMBf3TYZigQC&pg=PT143 |title=The Encyclopedia of Dead Rock Stars |page=124 |publisher=Chicago Review Press |date=2008 |isbn=1556527543|accessdate=2009-11-20 }}</ref> Keen played the drums and sang the lead.\n\n==Production==\nTownshend produced the single,<ref>Dave Spencer, {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MXkF1c8uRsoC&pg=PA97 |title=A Smudge on My Lens, page 97 |publisher=Troubador Publishing Ltd |year=2008 |isbn=1906510784 |accessdate=23 February 2019}}</ref> arranged the strings, and played bass under the pseudonym Bijou Drains<ref>{{cite interview |last=Townshend |first=Pete |subjectlink=Pete Townshend |interviewer=[[Liz Kershaw]] |title=Liz Kershaw, BBC 6music |publisher=BBC Radio|date=November 16, 2019 }}</ref>. Originally titled \"Revolution\" but later renamed to avoid confusion with [[the Beatles]]' 1968 [[Revolution (Beatles song)|song of the same name]], \"Something in the Air\" captured post-[[flower power]] rebellion, marrying McCulloch's sweeping acoustic and glowing electric guitars, Keen's powerful drumming and yearning falsetto, and Newman's felicitous piano solo.\n\nThe song, beginning in [[E major]], has three key changes, its second verse climbing to [[F-sharp major]], and, via a roundabout transition, goes down to [[C major]] for Newman's barrelhouse piano solo. Following this, the last verse is, like the second, a tone above the previous verse, closing the song in [[A-flat major]].\n\n==Reception==\nThe single reached No. 1 in the UK Singles Chart just three weeks after release, holding off [[Elvis Presley]] in the process. The scale of the song's success surprised everyone and there were no plans to promote Thunderclap Newman with live performances. Eventually a line-up - augmented by  Jim Pitman-Avory on bass and McCulloch's elder brother Jack on drums - played a handful of gigs. Personal records say the band played live only five times, although Keen referred to a two-month tour, playing \"everywhere\". In the UK, a follow-up single, \"Accidents\", came out only in May 1970 and charted at No. 46 for a week. An album, ''Hollywood Dream'', peaked in ''[[Billboard magazine|Billboard]]'' at No. 163. Thus, the song and the band were forever linked as a [[one hit wonder]]. [[Labelle]] recorded an emotional cover of it alongside \"[[The Revolution Will Not Be Televised]]\" by [[Gil Scott-Heron]] for their 1973 album, ''[[Pressure Cookin']]''.\n\n==Personnel==\n*[[Speedy Keen]] - [[double tracking|double-tracked]] lead vocal, drums\n*[[Jimmy McCulloch]] - lead and rhythm guitars\n*[[Pete Townshend]] - bass guitar (credited to \"Bijou Drains\"), orchestral arrangement\n*Andy \"Thunderclap\" Newman - piano, lead vocals on \"Wilhelmina\"\n\n==Chart performance (Thunderclap Newman version)==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1969)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Germany|13|artist=Thunderclap Newman|song=Something in the Air }}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|9|artist=Thunderclap Newman|song=Something in the Air }}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UKsinglesbyname|1|artist=Thunderclap Newman|song=Something in the Air}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardhot100|37|artist=Thunderclap Newman|song=Something in the Air }}\n|}\n\n==Appearance in other media==\n\"Something in the Air\" by Thunderclap Newman appeared on the soundtracks of several films, such as ''[[The Magic Christian (film)|The Magic Christian]]'' (1969), which helped the single reach No. 37 in the United States, and ''[[The Strawberry Statement (film)|The Strawberry Statement]]'' (1970), which prompted a reissue of the single that \"bubbled under\" the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 at No. 120. It later appeared in ''[[Kingpin (1996 film)|Kingpin]]'' (1996), ''[[Almost Famous]]'' (2000), ''[[The Dish]]'' (2000), and ''[[The Girl Next Door (2004 film)|The Girl Next Door]]'' (2004). It also appeared on and was the title of the second disc in the Deluxe Edition of the ''[[Easy Rider (soundtrack)|Easy Rider]]'' soundtrack.\n\n\"Something in the Air\" has been used extensively in television, most notably on an advertisement for [[British Airways]] which featured [[PJ O'Rourke]]. The song also appeared in a [[retro]] [[Television advertisement|TV advert]] for the [[Austin Mini]] in the early 1990s, featuring 1960s fashion model ''[[Twiggy]]''. More recently, a version of the song was used in the advertisements for the mobile phone service provider [[TalkTalk Group|TalkTalk]]. (A similar advert for TalkTalk shown at the beginning of advert breaks during ''[[Big Brother (UK)|Big Brother]]'' features the opening bars). The song was featured in a number of episodes of 1960s-set UK police series ''[[Heartbeat (UK TV series)|Heartbeat]]''. It is also used as the 'on hold' music for The Carphone Warehouse, of which Talk Talk is a part. The song was also featured in the pilot episode of the American television show ''[[Aliens in America]]'' and in the third-season episode ''[[Creative Writing (My Name Is Earl)|Bad Earl]]'' of ''[[My Name Is Earl]]''.  A version of the song recorded by [[Ocean Colour Scene]] was previously used by telephone provider [[Ionica (company)|Ionica]]. In 2008, this song appeared in a [[Coca-Cola]] commercial in [[Taiwan]]. It was also recently used in an episode of ''[[Prime Suspect 1973]]''.\n\n==Musical quotation==\n\"Something in the Air\" features a short burst of ''[[La Marseillaise]]'' - the national anthem of France. The ''revolution'' reference in the song's lyrics has subtly been hinted at in the synthesised brass arrangement from 3'30\". ''La Marseillaise'' also features in the ''[[1812 Overture]]'' by [[Pyotr Ilyich Tchaikovsky]] and in the opening of the [[Beatles]]' 1967 single [[All You Need Is Love]].\n\n==Covers==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Something in the Air\n| cover      = Something in the air tom petty.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Tom Petty and the Heartbreakers]]\n| album      = [[Greatest Hits (Tom Petty album)|Greatest Hits]]\n| released   = January 31, 1994\n| format     =\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      =\n| length     = 3:17\n| label      = [[MCA Inc.|MCA]]\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Speedy Keen]]}}\n| producer   = [[Rick Rubin]]\n| prev_title = [[Mary Jane's Last Dance]]\n| prev_year  = 1993\n| next_title = [[You Don't Know How It Feels]]\n| next_year  = 1994\n}}\nThe song has been covered by a number of artists, including:\n* The [[Mandrake Memorial]] in 1969\n* [[Labelle]] in 1973\n* [[Herbie Mann]] in 1974\n* [[Simon Park]] in 1974\n* [[Gamma (band)|Gamma]] in 1980\n* [[Eurythmics]] in 1985\n* [[Fish (singer)|Fish]] in 1991\n* [[The Lightning Seeds]] and [[Trip Shakespeare]] in 1992\n* [[Tom Petty and the Heartbreakers]] in 1994\n* [[U.K. Subs]] in 2000\n* [[The Superjesus]] in 2001\n* [[Elbow (band)|Elbow]] and [[Wellwater Conspiracy]] in 2003\n* [[Wilco]] live in late 2004 and throughout 2005 \n* [[Hayley Sanderson]] in 2006{{Citation needed|date=November 2009}}\n* [[Donald Fagen]] with the [[Dukes of September]]\n* [[Polyphonic Spree]] live since 2010\n* New Zealand/Australian band [[Dragon (band)|Dragon]] covered the song on their album, ''[[It's All Too Beautiful (album)|It's All Too Beautiful]]'' (2011). \n* [[Dixie Chicks]] live on select final dates of the [[DCX MMXVI World Tour]] in 2017.\n* [[Luna]] on their 2019 album 'Postscripts'. Lead guitarist Sean Eden on vocals. \n\n===Tom Petty's version===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1994)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Canadian ''RPM'' Top Singles\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|26\n|-\n|UK Singles Chart\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|53\n|-\n|U.S. ''Billboard'' [[Hot Mainstream Rock Tracks|Album Rock Tracks]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|19\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1969 singles]]\n[[Category:Debut singles]]\n[[Category:UK Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Labelle songs]]\n[[Category:Protest songs]]\n[[Category:Thunderclap Newman songs]]\n[[Category:Tom Petty songs]]\n[[Category:Track Records singles]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Pete Townshend]]\n[[Category:1969 songs]]\n", "name_user": "GoingBatty", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 - Repaired 1 link to disambiguation page -(You can help)-Luna/WP:WCWproject (Reference before punctuation)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Something_in_the_Air"}
{"title_page": "Anniyur Abathsahayeswarar Temple", "text_new": "[[File:Anniyur Abathsahayeswarar Temple1.jpg|200x200px|right|The entrance of the temple|thumb]]\n''' Anniyur Abathsahayeswarar Temple''' (\u0baa\u0bca\u0ba9\u0bcd\u0ba9\u0bc2\u0bb0\u0bcd \u0b86\u0baa\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0b9a\u0b95\u0bbe\u0baf\u0bc7\u0b9a\u0bc1\u0bb5\u0bb0\u0bb0\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bcb\u0baf\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bcd) is a [[Hindu temple]] located at Ponnur in [[Nagapattinam district]] of [[Tamil Nadu]], [[India]]. The historical name of the place is  Tiru Anniyur.<ref>[http://temple.dinamalar.com/en/new_en.php?id=217 Sri Abathsahayeswarar temple]</ref>  The presiding deity is [[Shiva]]. He is called as Abathsahayeswarar. His consort is known as  Perianayaki.\n\n== Significance ==\n[[File:Anniyur Abathsahayeswarar Temple2.jpg|left|100x150px|thumb|vimana of Presiding deity]]\n[[File:Anniyur Abathsahayeswarar Temple3.jpg|left|100x150px|thumb|vimana of Amman shrine]]\nIt is one of the shrines of the 275 [[Paadal Petra Sthalams]] - [[Shiva Temples of Tamil Nadu#Sthalams|Shiva Sthalams]] glorified in the early medieval ''[[Tevaram]]'' poems by Tamil Saivite [[Nayanars]] [[Tirugnanasambandar]] and [[Tirunavukkarasar]].\n\n== Literary mention ==\nGnanasambandar describes the feature of the deity of Anniyur as:<ref>Gnanasambandar Tevaram, I: 96: 3</ref> \n{{cquote|\u0ba8\u0bc0\u0ba4\u0bbf \u0baa\u0bc7\u0ba3\u0bc1\u0bb5\u0bc0\u0bb0\u0bcd, \u0b86\u0ba4\u0bbf \u0baf\u0ba9\u0bcd\u0ba9\u0bbf\u0baf\u0bc2\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0b9a\u0bcd<br>\n\u0b9a\u0bcb\u0ba4\u0bbf \u0ba8\u0bbe\u0bae\u0bae\u0bc7, \u0b93\u0ba4\u0bbf \u0baf\u0bc1\u0baf\u0bcd\u0bae\u0bcd\u0bae\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bc7.}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{cite web|title= Sri Abathsahayeswarar temple |url= http://temple.dinamalar.com/en/new_en.php?id=217 |publisher =[[Dinamalar]]}}\n* {{cite web|title= Aabhathsagayeswarar Temple, Tiru Anniyur\n |url= http://www.shivatemples.com/nofc/nc22.php |publisher=Shiva Temples of Tamilnadu, Paadal Petra Sivasthalangal}}\n\n{{coord missing|Tamil Nadu}}\n\n[[Category:Shiva temples in Nagapattinam district]]\n[[Category:Padal Petra Stalam]]\n\n\n{{India-Hindu-temple-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:Anniyur Abathsahayeswarar Temple1.jpg|200x200px|right|The entrance of the temple|thumb]]\n''' Anniyur Abathsahayeswarar Temple''' (\u0baa\u0bca\u0ba9\u0bcd\u0ba9\u0bc2\u0bb0\u0bcd \u0b86\u0baa\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0b9a\u0b95\u0bbe\u0baf\u0bc7\u0b9a\u0bc1\u0bb5\u0bb0\u0bb0\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bcb\u0baf\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bcd) is a [[Hindu temple]] located at Ponnur in [[Nagapattinam district]] of [[Tamil Nadu]], [[India]]. The historical name of the place is  Tiru Anniyur.<ref>[http://temple.dinamalar.com/en/new_en.php?id=217 Sri Abathsahayeswarar temple]</ref>  The presiding deity is [[Shiva]]. He is called as Abathsahayeswarar. His consort is known as  Perianayaki.\n\n== Significance ==\n[[File:Anniyur Abathsahayeswarar Temple2.jpg|left|100x150px|thumb|vimana of Presiding deity]]\n[[File:Anniyur Abathsahayeswarar Temple3.jpg|left|100x150px|thumb|vimana of Amman shrine]]\nIt is one of the shrines of the 275 [[Paadal Petra Sthalams]] - [[Shiva Temples of Tamil Nadu#Sthalams|Shiva Sthalams]] glorified in the early medieval ''[[Tevaram]]'' poems by Tamil Saivite [[Nayanars]] [[Tirugnanasambandar]] and [[Tirunavukkarasar]].\n\n== Literary Mention ==\nGnanasambandar describes the feature of the deity of Anniyur as:<ref>Gnanasambandar Tevaram, I: 96: 3</ref> \n{{cquote|\u0ba8\u0bc0\u0ba4\u0bbf \u0baa\u0bc7\u0ba3\u0bc1\u0bb5\u0bc0\u0bb0\u0bcd, \u0b86\u0ba4\u0bbf \u0baf\u0ba9\u0bcd\u0ba9\u0bbf\u0baf\u0bc2\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0b9a\u0bcd<br>\n\u0b9a\u0bcb\u0ba4\u0bbf \u0ba8\u0bbe\u0bae\u0bae\u0bc7, \u0b93\u0ba4\u0bbf \u0baf\u0bc1\u0baf\u0bcd\u0bae\u0bcd\u0bae\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bc7.}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{cite web|title= Sri Abathsahayeswarar temple |url= http://temple.dinamalar.com/en/new_en.php?id=217 |publisher =[[Dinamalar]]}}\n* {{cite web|title= Aabhathsagayeswarar Temple, Tiru Anniyur\n |url= http://www.shivatemples.com/nofc/nc22.php |publisher=Shiva Temples of Tamilnadu, Paadal Petra Sivasthalangal}}\n\n{{coord missing|Tamil Nadu}}\n\n[[Category:Shiva temples in Nagapattinam district]]\n[[Category:Padal Petra Stalam]]\n\n{{India-Hindu-temple-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Titodutta", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,MOS:HEADCAPS", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anniyur_Abathsahayeswarar_Temple"}
{"title_page": "Kenneth II of Scotland", "text_new": "{{Infobox royalty\n| name = Kenneth II\n| image = File:Kenneth II of Scotland (Holyrood).jpg\n| succession = [[King of Alba]]\n| reign = 971&ndash;995\n| predecessor = [[Cuil\u00e9n]] or [[Amla\u00edb, King of Scotland|Amla\u00edb]]\n| successor = [[Constantine III of Scotland|Constantine III]]\n| birth_date  = \n| death_date  = 995\n| death_place = [[Fettercairn]]?\n| issue = [[Malcolm II]], King of Alba<br />[[Boite mac Cin\u00e1eda]]?<br />D\u00fangal?<br />[[Suibne mac Cin\u00e1eda|Suibne]]?\n| house = [[House of Alpin|Alpin]]\n| father = [[Malcolm I]], King of Alba\n}}\n'''Cin\u00e1ed mac Ma\u00edl Coluim''' ([[Scottish Gaelic language|Modern Gaelic]]: ''Coinneach mac Mhaoil Chaluim''<ref>''Cin\u00e1ed mac Ma\u00edl Coluim'' is the Mediaeval Gaelic form.</ref> [[Anglicisation|anglicised]] as '''Kenneth II''', and nicknamed '''An Fionnghalach''', \"The Fratricide\";<ref>Skene, ''Chronicles'', p. 96.</ref> died 995) was [[Kingdom of Scotland|King of Scots]] (''[[Kingdom of Alba|Alba]]''). The  son of [[Malcolm I of Scotland|Malcolm I]] (M\u00e1el Coluim mac Domnaill), he succeeded [[Cuil\u00e9n|King Cuil\u00e9n]] (Cuil\u00e9n mac Iduilb) on the latter's death at the hands of [[Rhydderch ap Dyfnwal]] in 971.\n\n==Primary sources==\nThe ''[[Chronicle of the Kings of Alba]]'' was compiled in Kenneth's reign, but many of the place names mentioned are entirely corrupt, if not fictitious.<ref>Duncan, p. 21.</ref> Whatever the reality, the Chronicle states that \"[h]e immediately plundered <nowiki>[</nowiki>[[Kingdom of Strathclyde|Strathclyde]]<nowiki>]</nowiki> in part. Kenneth's infantry were slain with very great slaughter in Moin Uacoruar.\" The Chronicle further states that Kenneth plundered [[Northumbria]] three times, first as far as Stainmore, then to ''Cluiam'' and lastly to the [[River Dee, Wales|River Dee]] by [[Chester]]. These raids may belong to around 980, when the ''[[Anglo-Saxon Chronicle]]'' records attacks on [[Cheshire]].<ref>''ESSH'', p. 512; Duncan, p.25.</ref>\n\nIn 973, the ''[[Chronicle of Melrose]]'' reports that Kenneth, with [[M\u00e1el Coluim I of Strathclyde|M\u00e1el Coluim I]] (M\u00e1el Coluim mac Domnaill), the [[King of Strathclyde]], \"Maccus, king of very many islands\" (i.e. Magnus Haraldsson ([[Maccus mac Arailt]]), [[King of Mann and the Isles]]) and other kings, [[Wales|Welsh]] and [[Norsemen|Norse]], came to [[Chester]] to acknowledge the overlordship of the English king [[Edgar of England|Edgar the Peaceable]]<ref>''ESSH'', pp. 478&ndash;479; ''SAEC'', pp. 75&ndash;78.</ref> at [[King Edgar's council at Chester|a council in Chester]]. It may be that Edgar here regulated the frontier between the southern lands of the kingdom of Alba and the northern lands of his English kingdom. [[Cumbria]] was English, the western frontier lay on the [[Solway Firth|Solway]]. In the east, the frontier lay somewhere in later [[Lothian]], south of [[Edinburgh]].<ref>Duncan, pp.24&ndash;25.</ref>\n\nThe ''[[Annals of Tigernach]]'', in an aside, name three of the [[Mormaer]]s of Alba in Kenneth's reign in entry in 976: [[Cellach mac F\u00edndgaine]], [[Cellach mac Baireda]] and [[Donnchad mac Morga\u00ednd]]. The third of these, if not an error for Domnall mac Morga\u00ednd, is very likely a brother of Domnall, and thus the [[Mormaer of Moray]]. The Mormaerdoms or kingdoms ruled by the two Cellachs cannot be identified.<!--This could well be original research since I have lost the reference, if any, on which it is based.-->\n\nThe feud which had persisted since the death of [[Indulf of Scotland|King Indulf]] (Idulb mac Causant\u00edn) between his descendants and Kenneth's family persisted. In 977 the ''[[Annals of Ulster]]'' report that \"Amla\u00edb mac Iduilb <nowiki>[</nowiki>[[Amla\u00edb, King of Scotland|Amla\u00edb]], son of Indulf<nowiki>]</nowiki>, King of Scotland, was killed by Cin\u00e1ed mac Domnaill.\" The ''Annals of Tigernach'' give the correct name of Amla\u00edb's killer: ''Cin\u00e1ed mac Ma\u00edl Coluim'', or Kenneth II. Thus, even if only for a short time, Kenneth had been overthrown by the brother of the previous king.<ref>Duncan, pp. 21&ndash;22; ''ESSH'', p. 484.</ref>\n\n[[Adam of Bremen]] tells that [[Sweyn I of Denmark|Sweyn Forkbeard]] found exile in Scotland at this time, but whether this was with Kenneth, or one of the other kings in Scotland, is unknown. Also at this time, ''[[Njal's Saga]]'', the ''[[Orkneyinga Saga]]'' and other sources recount wars between \"the Scots\" and the Northmen, but these are more probably wars between [[Sigurd Hlodvisson]], [[Earl of Orkney]], and the Mormaers, or Kings, of Moray.<ref>See ''ESSH'', pp. 483&ndash;484 & 495&ndash;502.</ref>\n\nThe Chronicle says that Kenneth founded a great monastery at [[Brechin]].\n\nKenneth was killed in 995, the ''Annals of Ulster'' say \"by deceit\" and the ''Annals of Tigernach'' say \"by his subjects\". Some later sources, such as the ''[[Chronicle of Melrose]]'',  [[John of Fordun]] and [[Andrew of Wyntoun]] provide more details, accurately or not. The simplest account is that he was killed by his own men in [[Fettercairn]], through the treachery of Finnguala (also called Fimberhele or Fenella), daughter of [[Cuncar of Angus|Cuncar]], [[Mormaer of Angus]], in revenge for the killing of her only son.<ref>The name of Cuncar's daughter is given as Fenella, Finele or Sibill in later sources. John of Fordun credits [[Constantine III of Scotland|Constantine III]] (Causant\u00edn mac Cuil\u00e9n) and [[Kenneth III of Scotland|Kenneth III]] (Cin\u00e1ed mac Duib) with the planning, claiming that Kenneth II planned to change the laws of succession. See ''ESSH'', pp. 512&ndash;515.</ref>\n\nThe ''[[Prophecy of Berch\u00e1n]]'' adds little to our knowledge, except that it names Kenneth \"the kinslayer\", and states he died in [[Strathmore, Angus and Perth & Kinross|Strathmore]].<ref>''ESSH'', p. 516.</ref>\n\n==Children==\n\nKenneth's son [[Malcolm II of Scotland|Malcolm II]] (M\u00e1el Coluim mac Cin\u00e1eda)  was later king of Alba. Kenneth may have had a second son, named either D\u00fangal or Gille Coemg\u00e1in.<ref>''[[Annals of the Four Masters]]'', s.a. 998: \"D\u00fangal Cin\u00e1ed's son, was killed by Gille Coemg\u00e1in, Cin\u00e1ed's son.\" It is not clear if the Cin\u00e1eds (Kenneths) referred to are Cin\u00e1ed mac Ma\u00edl Coluim (Kenneth II) or his nephew and namesake Cin\u00e1ed mac Duib (Kenneth III). Smyth, pp. 221&ndash;222, makes D\u00fangal following ''ESSH'' p. 580.</ref> Sources differ as to whether [[Boite mac Cin\u00e1eda]] should be counted a son of Kenneth II or of Kenneth III (Cin\u00e1ed mac Duib).<ref>Compare Duncan, p.345 and Lynch (ed), Genealogies, at about p. 680. See also ''ESSH'', p. 580.</ref> Another son of Kenneth may have been [[Suibne mac Cin\u00e1eda]], a king of the ''[[Gall Gaidheil]]'' who died in 1034.\n\n==Interpretation==\nKenneth's rival [[Amla\u00edb, King of Scotland]] is omitted by the ''[[Chronicle of the Kings of Alba]]'' and later Scottish king-lists. The Irish [[Annals of Tigernach]] appear to better reflect contemporary events. Amla\u00edb could be a direct predecessor of Kenneth who suffered [[damnatio memoriae]], or the rival king recognized in parts of Scotland. A period of divided kingship appears likely.<ref name=\"Woolf\">Woolf (2007), p. 205-206</ref>\n\nAmla\u00edb was the heir of his brother [[Cuil\u00e9n]], who was killed in a hall-burning. He might have served as a regent north of the [[River Forth]], during the absence of his brother. Kenneth was brother to the deceased [[Dub, King of Scotland]] and was most likely an exile. He could claim the throne due to the support of friends and maternal kin. He was likely older and more experienced than his rival king.<ref name=\"Woolf\">Woolf (2007), p. 205-206</ref> Amla\u00edb is the Gaelic form of \u00d3l\u00e1fr, suggesting maternal descent from [[Norsemen]]. He could possibly claim descent from the [[U\u00ed \u00cdmair]] dynasty. Alex Woolf suggests he was a grandson of [[Amla\u00edb Cuar\u00e1n]], [[Kingdom of Dublin|King of Dublin]] or his cousin [[Olaf Guthfrithson]], which suggests his own group of supporters.<ref name=\"Woolf\">Woolf (2007), p. 205-206</ref>\n\n==Death==\nAccording to [[John of Fordun]] (14th century), Kenneth II of Scotland (reigned 971-995) attempted to change the succession rules, allowing \"''the nearest survivor in blood to the deceased king to succeed''\", thus securing the throne for his own descendants. He reportedly did so to specifically exclude Constantine (III) and Kenneth (III), called Gryme in this source. The two men then jointly conspired against him, convincing [[Lady Finella]], daughter of [[Cuncar of Angus|Cuncar]], [[Mormaer of Angus]], to kill the king. She reportedly did so to achieve personal revenge, as Kenneth II had killed her own son. Entries in ''the Chronicles of the Picts and Scots'', collected by [[William Forbes Skene]], provide the account of Finnela killing Kenneth II in revenge, but not her affiliation to Constantine or his cousins. These entries date to the 12th and 13th centuries.<ref>{{harvnb|Cawley|2011|loc=[http://fmg.ac/Projects/MedLands/SCOTLAND.htm#_Toc253996179 Malcolm]}}.Listing includes all kings descended from him, excluding Kenneth III.</ref><ref>The name of Cuncar's daughter is given as Fenella, Finele or Sibill in later sources. John of Fordun credits Constantine III (Causant\u00edn mac Cuil\u00e9n) and Kenneth III (Cin\u00e1ed mac Duib) with the planning, claiming that Kenneth II planned to change the laws of succession. See ''ESSH'', pp. 512&ndash;515.</ref> The [[Annals of Ulster]] simply record \"Cinaed son of Mael Coluim [Kenneth, son of Malcolm], king of Scotland, was deceitfully killed\", with no indication of who killed him.<ref>{{harvnb|Cawley|2011|loc=[http://fmg.ac/Projects/MedLands/SCOTLAND.htm#_Toc253996179 Malcolm I]}}.Listing includes all kings descended from him, excluding Kenneth III.</ref><ref name=\"Annals of Ulster\">[http://www.ucc.ie/celt/published/T100001A/ Annals of Ulster, online translation. Entry U995.1]</ref>\n\nIn the account of John of Fordun, [[Constantine III of Scotland|Constantine III]] and Gryme were \"plotting unceasingly the death of the king and his son\". One day, Kenneth II and his companions went hunting into the woods, \"at no great distance from his own abode\". The hunt took him to [[Fettercairn]], where Finella resided. She approached him to proclaim her loyalty and invited him to visit her residence, whispering into his ear that she had information about a conspiracy plot. She managed to lure him to \"an out-of-the-way little cottage\", where a [[booby trap]] was hidden. Inside the cottage was a statue, connected by strings to a number of [[crossbow]]s. If anyone touched or moved the statue, he would trigger the crossbows and fall victim to their arrows. Kenneth II gently touched the statue and \"was shot through by arrows sped from all sides, and fell without uttering another word.\" Finella escaped through the woods and managed to join her [[abettor]]s, Constantine III and Gryme. The hunting companions soon discovered the bloody king. They were unable to locate Finella, but burned Fettercairn to the ground.<ref name=\"Skene\">[https://archive.org/details/johnoffordunschr00fordrich Skene, John of Fordun's Chronicle of the Scottish nation, Book IV, Chapters XXXII-XXXIV (32-34), pages 165-169]</ref> Smyth dismisses the elaborate plotting and the mechanical contraption as mere fables, but accepts the basic details of the story, that the succession plans of Kenneth II caused his assassination.<ref name=\"Smyth2\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=mxxwmg48bFgC&pg=PA226 Smyth, Warlords and Holy Men: Scotland AD 80-1000, p. 224-225]</ref> [[Alan Orr Anderson]] raised his own doubts concerning the story of  Finella, which he considered \"semi-mythical\". He noted that the feminine name Finnguala or Findguala means \"white shoulders\", but suggested it derived from \"find-ela\" (white swan). The name figures in toponyms such as Finella Hill (near [[Fordoun]]) and Finella Den (near [[St Cyrus]]), while local tradition in The Mearns ([[Kincardineshire]]) has Finella walking atop the treetops from one location to the other. Anderson thus theorized that Finella could be a mythical figure, suggesting she was a local [[Water deity|stream-goddess]].<ref name=\"Anderson\">[https://archive.org/details/cu31924028144313 Anderson, Early sources of Scottish history, A.D. 500 to 1286, p. 515]</ref> A later passage of John of Fordun mentions Finele as mother of [[Macbeth, King of Scotland]] (reigned 1040\u20131057), but this is probably an error based on the similarity of names. Macbeth was son of [[Findl\u00e1ech of Moray]], not of a woman called Finella.<ref name=\"Anderson\"/><ref name=\"Skene4\">[https://archive.org/details/johnoffordunschr00fordrich Skene, John of Fordun's Chronicle of the Scottish nation, Book IV, Chapters XLIV (44), pages 180]</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==References==\n''For primary sources see also '' '''External links''' ''below.''\n{{refbegin}}\n* [[Alan Orr Anderson|Anderson, Alan Orr]], ''Early Sources of Scottish History A.D 500&ndash;1286'', volume 1. Reprinted with corrections. Paul Watkins, Stamford, 1990. {{ISBN|1-871615-03-8}}\n* Anderson, Alan Orr, ''Scottish Annals from English Chroniclers.'' D. Nutt, London, 1908.\n* Anon., ''Orkneyinga Saga: The History of the Earls of Orkney'', tr. Hermann P\u00e1lsson and Paul Edwards. Penguin, London, 1978. {{ISBN|0-14-044383-5}}\n* Duncan, A.A.M., ''The Kingship of the Scots 842\u20131292: Succession and Independence.'' Edinburgh University Press, Edinburgh, 2002. {{ISBN|0-7486-1626-8}}\n* Lynch, Michael (ed.), ''The Oxford Companion to Scottish History.'' Oxford UP, Oxford, 2002. {{ISBN|0-19-211696-7}}\n* Smyth, Alfred P. ''Warlords and Holy Men: Scotland AD 80-1000.'' Reprinted, Edinburgh: Edinburgh UP, 1998. {{ISBN|0-7486-0100-7}}\n* {{citation | last1=Woolf | first1=  Alex. | title=''From Pictland to Alba: 789 - 1070'' | chapter= Amla\u00edb son of Ildulb and Cinaed Son of Mael Coluim| year=2007 | publisher=[[Edinburgh University Press]]| isbn=978-0748612345| url =https://books.google.com/books?id=7d1SP6ztlq0C&pg=PA89 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://celt.ucc.ie/index.html CELT: Corpus of Electronic Texts] at [http://www.ucc.ie/ University College Cork] The '''Corpus of Electronic Texts''' includes the ''Annals of Ulster'', ''Tigernach'' and ''the Four Masters'', the ''Chronicon Scotorum'', as well as Genealogies, and various Saints' Lives. Most are translated into English, or translations are in progress\n*[http://www.kjhskj75z.talktalk.net/pictish.html#third The Chronicle of the Kings of Alba]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hou|[[House of Alpin]]||||995}}\n{{s-reg|}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Cuil\u00e9n of Scotland|Cuil\u00e9n]]|before2=[[Amla\u00edb, King of Scotland|Amla\u00edb mac Illuilb]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[King of Alba]]|years=971&ndash;995}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Constantine III of Scotland|Constantine III]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Pictish and Scottish Monarchs}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kenneth 02 Of Scotland}}\n[[Category:10th-century births]]\n[[Category:995 deaths]]\n[[Category:House of Alpin]]\n[[Category:Burials in Iona]]\n[[Category:Assassinated Scottish people]]\n[[Category:10th-century Scottish monarchs]]\n[[Category:10th-century murdered monarchs]]\n[[Category:Gaelic monarchs in Scotland]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox royalty\n| name = Kenneth II\n| image = File:Kenneth II of Scotland (Holyrood).jpg\n| succession = [[King of Alba]]\n| reign = 971&ndash;995\n| predecessor = [[Cuil\u00e9n]] or [[Amla\u00edb, King of Scotland|Amla\u00edb]]\n| successor = [[Constantine III of Scotland|Constantine III]]\n| birth_date  = \n| death_date  = 995\n| death_place = [[Fettercairn]]?\n| issue = [[Malcolm II]], King of Alba<br />[[Boite mac Cin\u00e1eda]]?<br />D\u00fangal?<br />[[Suibne mac Cin\u00e1eda|Suibne]]?\n| house = [[House of Alpin|Alpin]]\n| father = [[Malcolm I]], King of Alba\n}}\n'''Cin\u00e1ed mac Ma\u00edl Coluim''' ([[Scottish Gaelic language|Modern Gaelic]]: ''Coinneach mac Mhaoil Chaluim''<ref>''Cin\u00e1ed mac Ma\u00edl Coluim'' is the Mediaeval Gaelic form.</ref> [[Anglicisation|anglicised]] as '''Kenneth II''', and nicknamed '''An Fionnghalach''', \"The Fratricide\";<ref>Skene, ''Chronicles'', p. 96.</ref> died 995) was [[Kingdom of Scotland|King of Scots]] (''[[Kingdom of Alba|Alba]]''). The  son of [[Malcolm I of Scotland|Malcolm I]] (M\u00e1el Coluim mac Domnaill), he succeeded [[Cuil\u00e9n|King Cuil\u00e9n]] (Cuil\u00e9n mac Iduilb) on the latter's death at the hands of [[Rhydderch ap Dyfnwal]] in 971.\n\n==Primary sources==\nThe ''[[Chronicle of the Kings of Alba]]'' was compiled in Kenneth's reign, but many of the place names mentioned are entirely corrupt, if not fictitious.<ref>Duncan, p. 21.</ref> Whatever the reality, the Chronicle states that \"[h]e immediately plundered <nowiki>[</nowiki>[[Kingdom of Strathclyde|Strathclyde]]<nowiki>]</nowiki> in part. Kenneth's infantry were slain with very great slaughter in Moin Uacoruar.\" The Chronicle further states that Kenneth plundered [[Northumbria]] three times, first as far as Stainmore, then to ''Cluiam'' and lastly to the [[River Dee, Wales|River Dee]] by [[Chester]]. These raids may belong to around 980, when the ''[[Anglo-Saxon Chronicle]]'' records attacks on [[Cheshire]].<ref>''ESSH'', p. 512; Duncan, p.25.</ref>\n\nIn 973, the ''[[Chronicle of Melrose]]'' reports that Kenneth, with [[M\u00e1el Coluim I of Strathclyde|M\u00e1el Coluim I]] (M\u00e1el Coluim mac Domnaill), the [[King of Strathclyde]], \"Maccus, king of very many islands\" (i.e. Magnus Haraldsson ([[Maccus mac Arailt]]), [[King of Mann and the Isles]]) and other kings, [[Wales|Welsh]] and [[Norsemen|Norse]], came to [[Chester]] to acknowledge the overlordship of the English king [[Edgar of England|Edgar the Peaceable]]<ref>''ESSH'', pp. 478&ndash;479; ''SAEC'', pp. 75&ndash;78.</ref> at [[King Edgar's council at Chester|a council in Chester]]. It may be that Edgar here regulated the frontier between the southern lands of the kingdom of Alba and the northern lands of his English kingdom. [[Cumbria]] was English, the western frontier lay on the [[Solway Firth|Solway]]. In the east, the frontier lay somewhere in later [[Lothian]], south of [[Edinburgh]].<ref>Duncan, pp.24&ndash;25.</ref>\n\nThe ''[[Annals of Tigernach]]'', in an aside, name three of the [[Mormaer]]s of Alba in Kenneth's reign in entry in 976: [[Cellach mac F\u00edndgaine]], [[Cellach mac Baireda]] and [[Donnchad mac Morga\u00ednd]]. The third of these, if not an error for Domnall mac Morga\u00ednd, is very likely a brother of Domnall, and thus the [[Mormaer of Moray]]. The Mormaerdoms or kingdoms ruled by the two Cellachs cannot be identified.<!--This could well be original research since I have lost the reference, if any, on which it is based.-->\n\nThe feud which had persisted since the death of [[Indulf of Scotland|King Indulf]] (Idulb mac Causant\u00edn) between his descendants and Kenneth's family persisted. In 977 the ''[[Annals of Ulster]]'' report that \"Amla\u00edb mac Iduilb <nowiki>[</nowiki>[[Amla\u00edb, King of Scotland|Amla\u00edb]], son of Indulf<nowiki>]</nowiki>, King of Scotland, was killed by Cin\u00e1ed mac Domnaill.\" The ''Annals of Tigernach'' give the correct name of Amla\u00edb's killer: ''Cin\u00e1ed mac Ma\u00edl Coluim'', or Kenneth II. Thus, even if only for a short time, Kenneth had been overthrown by the brother of the previous king.<ref>Duncan, pp. 21&ndash;22; ''ESSH'', p. 484.</ref>\n\n[[Adam of Bremen]] tells that [[Sweyn I of Denmark|Sweyn Forkbeard]] found exile in Scotland at this time, but whether this was with Kenneth, or one of the other kings in Scotland, is unknown. Also at this time, ''[[Njal's Saga]]'', the ''[[Orkneyinga Saga]]'' and other sources recount wars between \"the Scots\" and the Northmen, but these are more probably wars between [[Sigurd Hlodvisson]], [[Earl of Orkney]], and the Mormaers, or Kings, of Moray.<ref>See ''ESSH'', pp. 483&ndash;484 & 495&ndash;502.</ref>\n\nThe Chronicle says that Kenneth founded a great monastery at [[Brechin]].\n\nKenneth was killed in 995, the ''Annals of Ulster'' say \"by deceit\" and the ''Annals of Tigernach'' say \"by his subjects\". Some later sources, such as the ''[[Chronicle of Melrose]]'',  [[John of Fordun]] and [[Andrew of Wyntoun]] provide more details, accurately or not. The simplest account is that he was killed by his own men in [[Fettercairn]], through the treachery of Finnguala (also called Fimberhele or Fenella), daughter of [[Cuncar of Angus|Cuncar]], [[Mormaer of Angus]], in revenge for the killing of her only son.<ref>The name of Cuncar's daughter is given as Fenella, Finele or Sibill in later sources. John of Fordun credits [[Constantine III of Scotland|Constantine III]] (Causant\u00edn mac Cuil\u00e9n) and [[Kenneth III of Scotland|Kenneth III]] (Cin\u00e1ed mac Duib) with the planning, claiming that Kenneth II planned to change the laws of succession. See ''ESSH'', pp. 512&ndash;515.</ref>\n\nThe ''[[Prophecy of Berch\u00e1n]]'' adds little to our knowledge, except that it names Kenneth \"the kinslayer\", and states he died in [[Strathmore, Angus and Perth & Kinross|Strathmore]].<ref>''ESSH'', p. 516.</ref>\n\n==Children==\n\nKenneth's son [[Malcolm II of Scotland|Malcolm II]] (M\u00e1el Coluim mac Cin\u00e1eda)  was later king of Alba. Kenneth may have had a second son, named either D\u00fangal or Gille Coemg\u00e1in.<ref>''[[Annals of the Four Masters]]'', s.a. 998: \"D\u00fangal Cin\u00e1ed's son, was killed by Gille Coemg\u00e1in, Cin\u00e1ed's son.\" It is not clear if the Cin\u00e1eds (Kenneths) referred to are Cin\u00e1ed mac Ma\u00edl Coluim (Kenneth II) or his nephew and namesake Cin\u00e1ed mac Duib (Kenneth III). Smyth, pp. 221&ndash;222, makes D\u00fangal following ''ESSH'' p. 580.</ref> Sources differ as to whether [[Boite mac Cin\u00e1eda]] should be counted a son of Kenneth II or of Kenneth III (Cin\u00e1ed mac Duib).<ref>Compare Duncan, p.345 and Lynch (ed), Genealogies, at about p. 680. See also ''ESSH'', p. 580.</ref> Another son of Kenneth may have been [[Suibne mac Cin\u00e1eda]], a king of the ''[[Gall Gaidheil]]'' who died in 1034.\n\n==Interpretation==\nKenneth's rival [[Amla\u00edb, King of Scotland]] is omitted by the ''[[Chronicle of the Kings of Alba]]'' and later Scottish king-lists. The Irish [[Annals of Tigernach]] appear to better reflect contemporary events. Amla\u00edb could be a direct predecessor of Kenneth who suffered [[damnatio memoriae]], or the rival king recognized in parts of Scotland. A period of divided kingship appears likely.<ref name=\"Woolf\">Woolf (2007), p. 205-206</ref>\n\nAmla\u00edb was the heir of his brother [[Cuil\u00e9n]], who was killed in a hall-burning. He might have served as a regent north of the [[River Forth]], during the absence of his brother. Kenneth was brother to the deceased [[Dub, King of Scotland]] and was most likely an exile. He could claim the throne due to the support of friends and maternal kin. He was likely older and more experienced than his rival king.<ref name=\"Woolf\">Woolf (2007), p. 205-206</ref> Amla\u00edb is the Gaelic form of \u00d3l\u00e1fr, suggesting maternal descent from [[Norsemen]]. He could possibly claim descent from the [[U\u00ed \u00cdmair]] dynasty. Alex Woolf suggests he was a grandson of [[Amla\u00edb Cuar\u00e1n]], [[Kingdom of Dublin|King of Dublin]] or his cousin [[Olaf Guthfrithson]], which suggests his own group of supporters.<ref name=\"Woolf\">Woolf (2007), p. 205-206</ref>\n\n==Death==\nAccording to [[John of Fordun]] (14th century), Kenneth II of Scotland (reigned 971-995) attempted to change the succession rules, allowing \"''the nearest survivor in blood to the deceased king to succeed''\", thus securing the throne for his own descendants. He reportedly did so to specifically exclude Constantine (III) and Kenneth (III), called Gryme in this source. The two men then jointly conspired against him, convincing [[Lady Finella]], daughter of [[Cuncar of Angus|Cuncar]], [[Mormaer of Angus]], to kill the king. She reportedly did so to achieve personal revenge, as Kenneth II had killed her own son. Entries in ''the Chronicles of the Picts and Scots'', collected by [[William Forbes Skene]], provide the account of Finnela killing Kenneth II in revenge, but not her affiliation to Constantine or his cousins. These entries date to the 12th and 13th centuries.<ref>{{harvnb|Cawley|2011|loc=[http://fmg.ac/Projects/MedLands/SCOTLAND.htm#_Toc253996179 Malcolm]}}.Listing includes all kings descended from him, excluding Kenneth III.</ref><ref>The name of Cuncar's daughter is given as Fenella, Finele or Sibill in later sources. John of Fordun credits Constantine III (Causant\u00edn mac Cuil\u00e9n) and Kenneth III (Cin\u00e1ed mac Duib) with the planning, claiming that Kenneth II planned to change the laws of succession. See ''ESSH'', pp. 512&ndash;515.</ref> The [[Annals of Ulster]] simply record \"Cinaed son of Mael Coluim [Kenneth, son of Malcolm], king of Scotland, was deceitfully killed\", with no indication of who killed him.<ref>{{harvnb|Cawley|2011|loc=[http://fmg.ac/Projects/MedLands/SCOTLAND.htm#_Toc253996179 Malcolm I]}}.Listing includes all kings descended from him, excluding Kenneth III.</ref><ref name=\"Annals of Ulster\">[http://www.ucc.ie/celt/published/T100001A/ Annals of Ulster, online translation. Entry U995.1]</ref>\n\nIn the account of John of Fordun, [[Constantine III of Scotland|Constantine III]] and Gryme were \"plotting unceasingly the death of the king and his son\". One day, Kenneth II and his companions went hunting into the woods, \"at no great distance from his own abode\". The hunt took him to [[Fettercairn]], where Finella resided. She approached him to proclaim her loyalty and invited him to visit her residence, whispering into his ear that she had information about a conspiracy plot. She managed to lure him to \"an out-of-the-way little cottage\", where a [[booby trap]] was hidden. Inside the cottage was a statue, connected by strings to a number of [[crossbow]]s. If anyone touched or moved the statue, he would trigger the crossbows and fall victim to their arrows. Kenneth II gently touched the statue and \"was shot though by arrows sped from all sides, and fell without uttering another word.\" Finella escaped through the woods and managed to join her [[abettor]]s, Constantine III and Gryme. The hunting companions soon discovered the bloody king. They were unable to locate Finella, but burned Fettercairn to the ground.<ref name=\"Skene\">[https://archive.org/details/johnoffordunschr00fordrich Skene, John of Fordun's Chronicle of the Scottish nation, Book IV, Chapters XXXII-XXXIV (32-34), pages 165-169]</ref> Smyth dismisses the elaborate plotting and the mechanical contraption as mere fables, but accepts the basic details of the story, that the succession plans of Kenneth II caused his assassination.<ref name=\"Smyth2\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=mxxwmg48bFgC&pg=PA226 Smyth, Warlords and Holy Men: Scotland AD 80-1000, p. 224-225]</ref> [[Alan Orr Anderson]] raised his own doubts concerning the story of  Finella, which he considered \"semi-mythical\". He noted that the feminine name Finnguala or Findguala means \"white shoulders\", but suggested it derived from \"find-ela\" (white swan). The name figures in toponyms such as Finella Hill (near [[Fordoun]]) and Finella Den (near [[St Cyrus]]), while local tradition in The Mearns ([[Kincardineshire]]) has Finella walking atop the treetops from one location to the other. Anderson thus theorized that Finella could be a mythical figure, suggesting she was a local [[Water deity|stream-goddess]].<ref name=\"Anderson\">[https://archive.org/details/cu31924028144313 Anderson, Early sources of Scottish history, A.D. 500 to 1286, p. 515]</ref> A later passage of John of Fordun mentions Finele as mother of [[Macbeth, King of Scotland]] (reigned 1040\u20131057), but this is probably an error based on the similarity of names. Macbeth was son of [[Findl\u00e1ech of Moray]], not of a woman called Finella.<ref name=\"Anderson\"/><ref name=\"Skene4\">[https://archive.org/details/johnoffordunschr00fordrich Skene, John of Fordun's Chronicle of the Scottish nation, Book IV, Chapters XLIV (44), pages 180]</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==References==\n''For primary sources see also '' '''External links''' ''below.''\n{{refbegin}}\n* [[Alan Orr Anderson|Anderson, Alan Orr]], ''Early Sources of Scottish History A.D 500&ndash;1286'', volume 1. Reprinted with corrections. Paul Watkins, Stamford, 1990. {{ISBN|1-871615-03-8}}\n* Anderson, Alan Orr, ''Scottish Annals from English Chroniclers.'' D. Nutt, London, 1908.\n* Anon., ''Orkneyinga Saga: The History of the Earls of Orkney'', tr. Hermann P\u00e1lsson and Paul Edwards. Penguin, London, 1978. {{ISBN|0-14-044383-5}}\n* Duncan, A.A.M., ''The Kingship of the Scots 842\u20131292: Succession and Independence.'' Edinburgh University Press, Edinburgh, 2002. {{ISBN|0-7486-1626-8}}\n* Lynch, Michael (ed.), ''The Oxford Companion to Scottish History.'' Oxford UP, Oxford, 2002. {{ISBN|0-19-211696-7}}\n* Smyth, Alfred P. ''Warlords and Holy Men: Scotland AD 80-1000.'' Reprinted, Edinburgh: Edinburgh UP, 1998. {{ISBN|0-7486-0100-7}}\n* {{citation | last1=Woolf | first1=  Alex. | title=''From Pictland to Alba: 789 - 1070'' | chapter= Amla\u00edb son of Ildulb and Cinaed Son of Mael Coluim| year=2007 | publisher=[[Edinburgh University Press]]| isbn=978-0748612345| url =https://books.google.com/books?id=7d1SP6ztlq0C&pg=PA89 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://celt.ucc.ie/index.html CELT: Corpus of Electronic Texts] at [http://www.ucc.ie/ University College Cork] The '''Corpus of Electronic Texts''' includes the ''Annals of Ulster'', ''Tigernach'' and ''the Four Masters'', the ''Chronicon Scotorum'', as well as Genealogies, and various Saints' Lives. Most are translated into English, or translations are in progress\n*[http://www.kjhskj75z.talktalk.net/pictish.html#third The Chronicle of the Kings of Alba]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hou|[[House of Alpin]]||||995}}\n{{s-reg|}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Cuil\u00e9n of Scotland|Cuil\u00e9n]]|before2=[[Amla\u00edb, King of Scotland|Amla\u00edb mac Illuilb]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[King of Alba]]|years=971&ndash;995}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Constantine III of Scotland|Constantine III]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Pictish and Scottish Monarchs}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kenneth 02 Of Scotland}}\n[[Category:10th-century births]]\n[[Category:995 deaths]]\n[[Category:House of Alpin]]\n[[Category:Burials in Iona]]\n[[Category:Assassinated Scottish people]]\n[[Category:10th-century Scottish monarchs]]\n[[Category:10th-century murdered monarchs]]\n[[Category:Gaelic monarchs in Scotland]]\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDeath:typo - quote change confirmed at reference given", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kenneth_II_of_Scotland"}
{"title_page": "Bikini Porn", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Bikini Porn\n| cover      = File:Bikini Porn cover.jpg\n| alt        = A woman with green hair is sitting on the grass by the poolside staring at the camera, wearing a dark top and white shorts. The single's title and the singer's name are written in white font.\n| type       = Single\n| artist     = [[Tove Lo]]\n| album      =\n| B-side     = Passion and Pain Taste the Same When I'm Weak\n| released   = {{Start date|2020|01|15|df=y}}\n| format     = {{hlist|[[Music download|Digital download]]|[[streaming]]}}\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Pop music|Pop]]\n| length     = 2:42\n| label      = [[Universal Music Group|Universal Music AB]]\n| writer     = {{hlist|Tove Lo|[[Finneas O'Connell]]|Jakob Hazell|Ludvig S\u00f6derberg|Svante Halldin}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|O'Connell|A Strut|[[Jack & Coke]]}}\n| prev_title = Sweettalk My Heart\n| prev_year  = 2019\n| next_title = Calling on Me\n| next_year  = 2020\n}}\n<!-- \"'''Bikini Porn'''\" is a single by Swedish singer [[Tove Lo]], released on 15 January 2020, on [[music download|download]] and [[streaming]] services. It features two songs, the title track and \"Passion and Pain Taste the Same When I'm Weak\". --> \n\"'''Bikini Porn'''\" is a song by Swedish singer and songwriter [[Tove Lo]], written by her alongside [[Finneas O'Connell|Finneas]], Jakob Hazell, Ludvig S\u00f6derberg and Svante Halldin. It was produced by Finneas, [[Jack & Coke]] and A Strut, who also handled the [[programming (music)|programming]]. \"Bikini Porn\" was released without previous announcement as a single on 15 January 2020, on [[music download|download]] and [[streaming]] services. The single also featured the track \"Passion and Pain Taste the Same When I'm Weak\", written by Lo and its producer Finneas.\n\n\"Bikini Porn\" is a [[pop music|pop]] song with a [[tropical music|tropical]] instrumentation. According to the singer, the title of the track means \"[[tan line]]s\" and its lyrics talk about \"letting go of your worries\". It received positive reviews from [[music journalism|music critics]], who complimented its composition and noted the contrast between the track and \"Passion and Pain Taste the Same When I'm Weak\". \"Bikini Porn\" had a minor commercial reception, peaking at number 79 in Sweden and number 35 on the [[Recorded Music NZ|Hot 40 Singles Chart]] in New Zealand. \n\nAn accompanying music video for \"Bikini Porn\", released on 17 January 2020, was directed by Moni Haworth and filmed in [[Hesperia, California|Hesperia]] and [[Victorville, California]]. Edited in a [[lo-fi]] and [[VHS]] style, it depicts the singer wearing different bikinis while dancing in various locations. It also features a cameo by Finneas in the last scene as an [[Uber]] driver. \n\"Bikini Porn\" was performed live for the first time during the opening show of the Sunshine Kitty Tour in [[Nashville, Tennessee]] on 3 February 2020.<ref name=\"tour\">{{cite web | url=https://www.tullahomanews.com/entertainment/national/tove-lo-opens-new-tour-with-party-like-atmosphere-in/article_ac5d09c2-478d-11ea-909d-7b86640596ea.html | title=Tove Lo opens new tour with party-like atmosphere in Nashville | work=Tullahoma News | date=4 February 2020 | accessdate=29 February 2020 | author=Birdsong, Zach | archive-url=http://archive.is/Rayjs | archive-date=29 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\n[[File:Finneas O'Connell 2019 by Glenn Francis.jpg|alt=A red-haired man wearing glasses, white shirt, gray suit and purple tie while staring at the camera.|160px|left|thumb|[[Finneas O'Connell|Finneas]], co-writer of \"Bikini Porn\".]]\nAccording to [[Tove Lo]], she wrote \"Bikini Porn\" while drinking [[champagne]] during a recording session, feeling she was emotionally \"in a happy place\".<ref name=\"muumuse\">{{cite web | url=https://muumuse.com/2020/01/tove-lo-bikini-porn.html/ | title='Bikini Porn': Tove Lo Shakes Her Disco Tits Around the Desert | publisher=[[MuuMuse]] | date=18 January 2020 | accessdate=22 February 2020 | author=Stern, Bradley}}</ref> She then showed the track to her team, who gave her a lukewarm response to it. Despite their comments, Lo contacted musician [[Finneas O'Connell|Finneas]] through mutual friends and sent him the song, asking him to produce it, which he accepted as he found it \"awesome\".<ref name=\"nylon\">{{cite web | url=https://nylon.com/tove-lo-on-grammys-finneas | title=Tove Lo Talks Her Latest Project With Finneas And The Grammys' Place In Pop Music | work=[[Nylon (magazine)|Nylon]] | date=30 January 2020 | accessdate=29 February 2020 | author=Lakshmin, Deepa}}</ref> She stated that Finneas gave the track the \"grit and weirdness and bopness\" that it needed and she felt honored and excited that he wanted to work with her.<ref name=\"outnow\">{{cite web | url=https://www.outnowmagazine.com/tove-lo-bikini-porn | title=Tove Lo Unveils Two New Songs, Produced by Finneas, 'bikini Porn' & 'passion and Pain Taste the Same When I'm Weak' | work=[[OUTNOW (ON Magazine)|OutNow]] | accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref> \n\nRegarding the collaboration, Finneas revealed on his [[Instagram]] account that he became a fan of Lo upon hearing her song \"[[Habits (Stay High)]]\" in 2014, and that \"Bikini Porn\" was the track he dreamed about producing for her.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.thelineofbestfit.com/news/latest-news/tove-lo-unveils-two-new-tracks-produced-by-billie-eilishs-brother-finneas | title=Tove Lo unveils two new tracks produced by Billie Eilish's brother FINNEAS | publisher=The Line of Best Fit | date=16 January 2020 | accessdate=22 February 2020 | author=Kenneally, Cerys}}</ref> The duo also wrote the [[Sentimental ballad|ballad]] \"Passion and Pain Taste the Same When I'm Weak\" together, of which Lo recalls telling Finneas, \"I love writing with you, you're bringing out this other side of me, I think, a lot of people try to push more of a happier way\".<ref name=\"beats\">{{cite web | url=https://music.apple.com/nl/station/1-15-20-tove-lo/ra.1495109430 | title=1/15/20: Tove Lo | publisher=[[Apple Music]] | accessdate=22 February 2020 | archive-url=http://archive.is/902nP | archive-date=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]], \"Bikini Porn\" was written by Lo, Finneas, Ludvig S\u00f6derberg, Jakob Hazell and Svante Halldin. Its production and [[Programming (music)|programming]] was handled by Finneas, [[Jack & Coke]] and A Strut. Meanwhile, \"Passion and Pain Taste the Same When I'm Weak\" was written by Lo alongside Finneas, with the latter also producing, programming and [[Audio engineer|engineering]] it. Serban Ghenea [[Mixing (music production)|mixed]] both tracks with the assistance of John Hannes, while [[Chris Gehringer]] [[Mastering engineer|mastered]] them. Finneas also produced the vocals and played the [[synthesizer]] and [[percussion instrument]]s for both songs.<ref name=\"tidal\" />\n\n== Composition ==\n\"Bikini Porn\" is an [[Glossary of music terminology#U|uptempo]]<ref name=\"jenesa\" /> [[pop music|pop]] song,<ref name=\"rel\"/> with a length of two minutes and forty-two seconds.<ref name=\"itu\" /> Its instrumentation incorporates a highly processed,<ref name=\"rel\"/> [[Tropical music|tropical]] [[Beat (music)|beat]] and backing vocals processed with [[vocoder]].<ref name=\"bbr\" /> Lo explained on [[Beats 1]] that the title of the track means \"[[tan line]]s\", adding that it reflects about \"living in the sun\" and the \"weird\" lifestyle in [[Los Angeles]] that she considers to be \"so dark and so fun\".<ref name=\"muumuse\" /> In another statement, she described \"Bikini Porn\" as \"a sexy and weird song about letting go of your worries\" where she also makes fun of herself.<ref name=\"muumuse\" /> Derrick Rossignol of [[Uproxx]] opined that Lo was singing about \"her success and enjoying a warm day\", as demonstrated in the lyrics \"All I do is drink champagne all day, all day, all day/ And I dance around my room naked, oh yeah, naked\".<ref name=\"uprx\">{{cite web | url=https://uproxx.com/pop/tove-lo-bikini-porn-passion-pain-taste-same-weak/ | title=Tove Lo Drops Two New Songs, 'Bikini Porn' And 'Passion And Pain Taste The Same When I'm Weak' | publisher=[[Uproxx]] | date=15 January 2020 | accessdate=28 February 2020 | author=Rossignol, Derrick}}</ref> Writing for [[MuuMuse]], Bradley Stern compared the track's composition to that of [[Billie Eilish]]'s \"[[Bad Guy (Billie Eilish song)|Bad Guy]]\" and the songs from [[Robyn (singer)|Robyn]]'s ''[[Body Talk (Robyn album)|Body Talk]]''.<ref name=\"muumuse\" /> \n\nOn the other hand, \"Passion and Pain Taste the Same When I'm Weak\", is a four-minutes [[ambient music|ambient]] [[Sentimental ballad|ballad]] with an instrumentation composed of [[background noise]] and [[Percussion instrument|percussion]].<ref name=\"jenesa\" /><ref name=\"itu\" /> It was described by Lo on Beats 1 as a \"beautiful, kind of, more poetic ballad\".<ref name=\"beats\" /> About the title, she told ''Nylon'' that she found passion and hate in a passionate relationship to be \"really close\", where \"all of a sudden, [that] turns into more pain than it does love\".<ref name=\"nylon\" /> Stephen Daw said that Lo \"laments on a dark period in her relationship\" in the lyrics, as exemplified in the verse, \"If you break my bones, I'mma hurt my soul, gonna fuck it out again and again\".<ref name=\"bbr\" /> Similarly, Rose Riddell of ''Coup de Main Magazine'' said Lo was \"reflecting on a dark time in a relationship\" in the lyrics of the track.<ref name=\"coup\" /> Patrick Clarke of ''NME'' noted it had a \"darker\" thematic than \"Bikini Porn\".<ref name=\"nmer\"/> Stern opined \"Passion and Pain Taste the Same When I'm Weak\" was \"more tender\" than \"Bikini Porn\" and noted on it some elements of Eilish's \"whisper-soft vulnerability and ominousness\" as well as Lo's \"emotional turbulence\".<ref name=\"muumuse\" /> Rossignol considered it \"slower and more somber in tone\" than \"Bikini Porn\", saying its lyrics talked about an \"ill-fated relationship\".<ref name=\"uprx\" />\n\n== Release ==\nIn a June 2019 interview with ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', Lo stated that she had written songs with Finneas, describing the session as \"awesome\" and praised his ability as a producer and writer.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8514806/tove-lo-talks-admiration-billie-eilish-video | title=Tove Lo Talks Admiration For Billie Eilish, How a 'Girls' Episode Inspired New Album Title 'Sunshine Kitty': Watch | work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | accessdate=22 February 2020 | author=Schiller, Rebecca}}</ref> In October of that year, she told ''[[NME]]'' that, \"We're fans of each others' music and he's a really good lyricist so it felt like a fresher, freer session \u2013 though I can't say anything about the songs\".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nme.com/big-reads/tove-lo-interview-sunshine-kitty-big-read-2553873 | title=The Big Read \u2013 Tove Lo: 'Sexuality is a fluid thing \u2013 it\u2019s hard to be just one way' | work=[[NME]] | date=4 October 2019 | accessdate=22 February 2020 | author=Ryan, Gary}}</ref> The next month, Finneas revealed to [[Radio.com]] that his collaboration with Lo would be released before April 2020.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.radio.com/music/pop/whats-next-for-grammy-nominee-finneas | title=Exclusive: What's Next for Grammy Nominee FINNEAS? | publisher=[[Radio.com]] | date=21 November 2019 | accessdate=22 February 2020 | author=Diehl, Bob}}</ref> On 24 December 2019, Lo posted the lyrics of an unreleased song to her [[Instagram]] account, using the [[hashtag]] \"bikiniporn\". Cerys Kenneally of [[The Line of Best Fit]] concluded the hashtag was the title of the new single.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.thelineofbestfit.com/news/latest-news/tove-lo-unveils-lyrics-for-upcoming-single | title=Tove Lo unveils lyrics for upcoming single | publisher=[[The Line of Best Fit]] | date=24 December 2019 | accessdate=22 February 2020 | author=Kenneally, Cerys}}</ref> On 15 January 2020, four months after releasing her fourth studio record ''[[Sunshine Kitty]]'',<ref name=\"variety\">{{cite web | url=https://variety.com/2020/music/news/tove-lo-finneas-billie-eilish-new-songs-1203468671/ | title=Tove Lo Drops Two New Songs With Billie Eilish\u2019s Brother Finneas | work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date=15 January 2020 | accessdate=22 February 2020 | author=Aswad, Jem}}</ref> Lo released, without any previous announcement,<ref name=\"variety\"/> the single \"Bikini Porn\", which featured the title track and \"Passion and Pain Taste the Same When I'm Weak\".<ref name=\"jenesa\">{{cite web | url=https://jenesaispop.com/2020/01/15/381366/tove-lo-le-roba-a-billie-eilish-a-su-hermano-finneas-para-un-nuevo-doble-single-bikini-porn/ | title=Tove Lo le 'roba' a Billie Eilish a su hermano FINNEAS para un nuevo doble single, 'Bikini Porn' | publisher=Jenesaispop | trans-title=Tove Lo 'steals' to Billie Eilish her brother FINNEAS for her new double-single, 'Bikini Porn' | date=15 January 2020 | accessdate=22 February 2020 | author=Guill\u00e9n, Ra\u00fal | language=Spanish}}</ref> It became available on both [[music download|download]] and [[streaming]] services,<ref name=\"rel\">{{cite web | url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/01/tove-lo-bikini-porn-passion-and-pain-taste-the-same-when-im-weak-stream/ | title=Tove Lo shares new songs 'Bikini Porn' and 'Passion and Pain Taste the Same When I'm Weak': Stream | work=[[Consequence of Sound]] | accessdate=15 February 2020 | author=Bacior, Robin}}</ref> via [[Universal Music Group|Universal Music AB]].<ref name=\"stereogum\">{{cite web | url=https://www.stereogum.com/2070173/tove-lo-bikini-porn-passion-and-pain-taste-the-same-when-im-weak/music/ | title=Tove Lo \u2013 'Bikini Porn' & 'Passion And Pain Taste The Same When I'm Weak' | publisher=[[Stereogum]] | date=15 January 2020 | accessdate=23 February 2020 | author=Rettig, James}}</ref> \n\nAccording to Lo, the reason why both songs were released together was to represent two sides of \"the extreme emotions of life\".<ref name=\"nylon\" /> She elaborated that the tracks show that she can be sexual and confident but also smart and poetic at the same time.<ref name=\"chi\">{{cite web | url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/music/ct-ott-tove-lo-riviera-chicago-0214-20200213-wlg7xa77qjeuddmoljtvjjvhmi-story.html | title=Tove Lo is provocative, and she isn't shy about it, none of which would matter if her music wasn\u2019t always on point | work=[[Chicago Tribune]] | date=13 February 2020 | accessdate=29 February 2020 | author=Hyman, Dan | archive-url=http://archive.is/d1PTf | archive-date=29 February 2020}}</ref> Some critics noted the difference in composition between \"Bikini Porn\" and \"Passion and Pain Taste the Same When I'm Weak\".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://onairwithryan.iheart.com/content/2020-01-16-listen-to-tove-los-two-new-tracks-with-billie-eilishs-brother-finneas/ | title=Listen to Tove Lo's Two New Tracks With Billie Eilish's Brother Finneas | publisher=[[On Air with Ryan Seacrest]] | date=17 January 2020 | accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref> Stephen Daw of ''Billboard'' described them as \"almost polar opposites of one another\",<ref name=\"bbr\">{{cite web | url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/pride/8548123/tove-lo-new-songs-finneas | title=Tove Lo Recruits Finneas for 2 New Surprise Tracks, Plus 'Bikini Porn' Video | work=Billboard | date=17 January 2020 | accessdate=27 February 2020 | author=Daw, Stephen}}</ref> while Rose Riddell of ''Coup de Main Magazine'' wrote both songs \"juxtapose each other emotionally and musically\".<ref name=\"coup\">{{cite web | url=https://www.coupdemainmagazine.com/tove-lo/16286 | title=Tove Lo shares new songs 'Bikini Porn' and 'Passion and Pain Taste the Same When I'm Weak'. | work=Coup de Main Magazine | date=16 January 2020 | accessdate=27 February 2020 | author=Riddell, Rose}}</ref> Similarly, Patrick Clarke of ''NME'' said that the tracks presented two different sides to Lo's music.<ref name=\"nmer\">{{cite web | url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/tove-lo-bikini-porn-passion-and-pain-taste-the-same-when-im-weak-finneas-2597235 | title=Tove Lo teams up with FINNEAS for two surprise songs, 'Bikini Porn' and 'Passion And Pain Taste The Same When I'm Weak' | work=NME | date=15 January 2020 | accessdate=27 February 2020 | author=Clarke, Patrick}}</ref> On the other hand, Mike Wass of [[Idolator (website)|Idolator]] said both songs reflected Finneas' minimal, [[indie pop|alternative]] sound.<ref name=\"idolator\">{{cite web | url=https://www.idolator.com/7905551/tove-lo-kicks-off-the-2020s-with-bikini-porn-and-passion-pain | title=Tove Lo Kicks Off The 2020s With 'Bikini Porn' And 'Passion & Pain' | publisher=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]] | date=17 January 2020 | accessdate=29 February 2020 | author=Wass, Mike}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\nBradley Stern of MuuMuse said \"Bikini Porn\" had \"earworm melodies and an underlying melancholy\" and compared it with Lo's previous singles, \"[[Disco Tits]]\" and \"[[Cool Girl]]\".<ref name=\"muumuse\" /> Madeline Roth of [[MTV News]] said the track sounded \"like a very, very early contender for song of the Summer\",<ref name=\"mtv\" /> while Patrick Clarke of ''NME'' deemed it as \"joyous\".<ref name=\"nmer\" /> Similarly, Claire Shaffer of ''[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]'' said \"Bikini Porn\" was a \"hedonist banger\" and also a \"very early contender for song of the Summer\".<ref name=\"rstr\">{{cite web | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/tove-lo-bikini-porn-finneas-938295/ | title=Tove Lo Releases Two Tracks With Billie Eilish's Brother Finneas | work=[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]] | date=15 January 2020 | accessdate=29 February 2020 | author=Shaffer, Claire}}</ref> Jordi Bardaj\u00ed of Jenesaispop called it a \"dancey, fun track\",<ref name=\"jenesavid\" /> while Ra\u00fal Guill\u00e9n of the same website opined the song could have been part of ''Sunshine Kitty'', adding that Finneas' contribution was notorious.<ref name=\"jenesa\" /> An editor of Scandipop said that, with \"Bikini Porn\", Lo was \"at her cheekiest\" point.<ref name=\"scandi\">{{cite web | url=https://www.scandipop.co.uk/video-tove-lo-bikini-porn/ | title=Video: Tove Lo - 'Bikini Porn' | publisher=Scandipop | date=23 January 2020 | accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref> Mike Wass of Idolator found the chorus of the song \"quirky\" as well as \"short and sweet and very, very catchy\".<ref name=\"idolator\" /> Rose Riddel of ''Coup de Main Magazine'' called it an \"upbeat empowering song\",<ref name=\"coup\" /> while Jem Aswad of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' deemed it as a \"bouncy\" and \"driving dancefloor track\".<ref name=\"variety\" /> Michael Love Michael of ''[[Paper (magazine)|Paper]]'' opined \"Bikini Porn\" was a \"sexy, empowered track\" and a \"[[tongue-in-cheek]] joke\" about Lo herself.<ref name=\"paper\">{{cite web | url=https://www.papermag.com/bops-only-alec-benjamin-2644845013.html | title=Bops Only: 10 Songs You Need to Start Your Weekend Right | work=[[Paper (magazine)|Paper]] | date=17 January 2020 | accessdate=29 February 2020}}</ref> Salvatore Maicki of ''[[The Fader]]'' wrote a positive review of the song, saying it \"feels fit for an unseasonably warm January, a tousled paean to living skimpier\".<ref name=\"fader\">{{cite web | url=https://www.thefader.com/2020/01/15/tove-lo-bikini-porn-finneas-new-single-passion-and-pain | title=Hear Tove Lo's fiery new single 'Bikini Porn' | work=[[The Fader]] | date=15 January 2020 | accessdate=29 February 2020 | author=Maicki, Salvatore}}</ref>\n\nIn Sweden, \"Bikini Porn\" debuted at number 76 on the [[Sverigetopplistan|Veckolista Singlar]],<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.sverigetopplistan.se/chart/41?dspy=2020&dspp=4 | title=Veckolista Singlar, vecka 4 | publisher=[[Sverigetopplistan]] | accessdate=23 February 2020 | archive-url=http://archive.is/kXYE7 | archive-date=23 February 2020|language=sv|trans-title=Weekly Singles chart, week 4}}</ref> for the week of 24 January 2020.<ref name=\"swe\" /> In New Zealand, \"Bikini Porn\" debuted at number 35 on the [[Official New Zealand Music Chart|Hot 40 Singles Chart]] during the week of 27 January 2020.<ref name=\"nz\">{{cite web | url=https://nztop40.co.nz/chart/hotsingles?chart=4811 | title=Hot 40 Singles | publisher=[[Official New Zealand Music Chart]] | accessdate=23 February 2020|archive-url=http://archive.is/Q1wpm|archive-date=23 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n\"Passion and Pain Taste the Same When I'm Weak\" also received some reviews from critics. Bardaj\u00ed called it \"more ambient and emotional\" than \"Bikini Porn\",<ref name=\"jenesavid\" /> while Guill\u00e9n compared it with the songs on Eilish's ''[[When We All Fall Asleep, Where Do We Go?]]''.<ref name=\"jenesa\" /> The Scandipop website considered the track a \"downbeat slice of melancholia\",<ref name=\"scandi\" /> while Wass deemed it as an \"experiment\".<ref name=\"idolator\" /> Maicki wrote that \"Passion and Pain Taste the Same When I'm Weak\" was \"the flip side\" to \"Bikini Porn\", adding it is the \"woozy comedown from the serotonin rush that preceded it\".<ref name=\"fader\" /> In a similar review, Shaffer said the song \"flips the party into a comedown\" and called it a \"woozy track that will sound great as a YouTube reverb remix\".<ref name=\"rstr\"/> Deepa Lakshmin of ''Nylon'' felt that Finneas' characteristic production style was evident on the song, adding that it was a \"quietly powerful\" track.<ref name=\"nylon\" />\n\n== Music video ==\n[[File:Bikini Porn mv.png|alt=A collage of singer Tove Lo dancing in different locations while wearing a bikini.|thumb|300px|right|The music video for \"Bikini Porn\" features Lo wearing bikinis and dancing in different locations, such as the backseat of an [[Uber]] car (''upper left''), a record store (''upper right''), the back of a trailer (''lower left'') and a gym (''lower right'').]]\nThe music video for \"Bikini Porn\" was directed by Moni Haworth and filmed in [[Hesperia, California|Hesperia]] and [[Victorville, California]],<ref name=\"victor\">{{cite web | url=https://www.vvng.com/swedish-artist-tove-lo-films-latest-video-bikini-porn-in-victorville-and-hesperia/ | title=Swedish artist Tove Lo films latest video 'Bikini Porn' in Victorville and Hesperia | work=Victor Valley News | date=17 January 2020 | accessdate=28 February 2020 | author=Valdez, Hugo}}</ref> with a crew of seven people. About the filming, Lo said that it was fun and bizarre to shoot, describing the clip as sexual and funny while not every scene is \"meant to be flattering\". Finneas, the track's co-producer and songwriter, makes a cameo as an [[Uber]] driver.<ref name=\"rsvideo\">{{cite web | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/tove-lo-bikini-porn-video-939106/ | title=Tove Lo Dances in Bizarre Lo-Fi Video for 'Bikini Porn' | work=Rolling Stone | date=17 January 2020 | accessdate=28 February 2020 | author=Shaffer, Claire}}</ref> On 10 January 2020, Lo posted four pictures on Instagram wearing a swimsuit in a desert, with the hashtag #bikiniporn, which led to speculation about a possible upcoming music video by the singer. Twenty-one hours later, the post garnered 81,000 likes and more than 460 comments.<ref name=\"inq\">{{cite web | url=https://www.inquisitr.com/5830594/tove-lo-pink-animal-print-swimsuit/ | title=Tove Lo Wears Pink Animal-Print Swimsuit & Teases Lyrics To Unreleased Song, 'Bikini Porn' | work=[[Inquisitr]] | date=10 January 2020 | accessdate=28 February 2020 | author=Magnocavallo, Fabio}}</ref> On 17 January 2020, Lo released the clip on digital platforms, and wrote a post on Instagram saying, \"Anyone shocked it's basically me running around in a bikini? Didn't think so.\"<ref name=\"victor\"/>\n\nThe music video, which was shot in a [[lo-fi]] and [[VHS]] style,<ref name=\"jenesavid\">{{cite web | url=https://jenesaispop.com/2020/01/19/381631/no-te-pierdas-tove-lo-desatada-no-puede-parar-de-bailar-en-el-video-de-bikini-porn/ | title=Tove Lo, desatada, la l\u00eda bailando en bikini en todas partes en el v\u00eddeo de 'Bikini Porn' | publisher=Jenesaispop | date=19 January 2020 | accessdate=28 February 2020 | author=Bardaj\u00ed, Jordi}}</ref><ref name=\"rsvideo\"/> depicts the singer wearing different bikinis while dancing on various locations, such as a desert, a gym and the back of a trailer.<ref name=\"victor\"/><ref name=\"rsvideo\"/> In one scene, she takes off her top and gets into a pool, paralleling the lyric \"Skinny dippin' in the pool with me\".<ref name=\"mtv\">{{cite web | url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3152954/tove-lo-bikini-porn-video-finneas/ | title=Tove Lo Takes An Awkward Uber Ride With Finneas In 'Bikini Porn' Video | work=[[MTV News]] | date=17 January 2020 | accessdate=28 February 2020 | author=Roth, Madeline}}</ref> Then, she starts dancing in a [[record shop]] while being watched by the employees, who eventually kick her out.<ref name=\"mtv\"/><ref name=\"jenesavid\"/><ref name=\"victor\"/> In the last scene, she appears dancing in the backseat of an Uber car driven by Finneas, who seems uncomfortable with her presence.<ref name=\"mtv\"/> About the plot, Lo said \"[It's] me in my own world, just living my life without caring what people think.\"<ref name=\"nylon\" /> \n\nCarolyn Droke of [[Uproxx]] opined that the clip \"compliments the track's upbeat energy\" and that it looked \"like a home video\".<ref name=\"upr\">{{cite web | url=https://uproxx.com/pop/tove-lo-bikini-porn-video/ | title=Tove Lo's 'Bikini Porn' Video Is A Fun Love Letter To The Swimsuit | publisher=[[Uproxx]] | date=17 January 2020 | accessdate=28 February 2020 | author=Droke, Carolyn}}</ref> ''Rolling Stone''{{'}}s Claire Shaffer called it \"bizarre\",<ref name=\"rsvideo\"/> while Jordi Bardaj\u00ed of Jenesaispop noted the singer was \"completely unleashed\" while showing her sensuality everywhere she went to in the plot.<ref name=\"jenesavid\"/> Madeline Roth of [[MTV News]] wrote the music video's highlight was the scene with Lo dancing in the backseat of the Uber car with Finneas as a driver.<ref name=\"mtv\"/> Bradley Stern of MuuMuse considered the plot \"fairly straightforward\", saying it encapsulated the \"blissful absurdity\" of the song.<ref name=\"muumuse\" /> Deepa Lakshmin of ''[[Nylon (magazine)|Nylon]]'' felt the clip was a \"sharp contrast\" to the one for \"[[Glad He's Gone]]\", the lead single from Lo's ''Sunshine Kitty'' album, which had a more expensive production. She also complimented Finneas' cameo, saying it was a \"fantastic bonus\".<ref name=\"nylon\" />\n\n== Track listing ==\n'''Digital download \u2013 \"Bikini Porn\" single'''<ref name=\"itu\"/>\n# \"Bikini Porn\" \u2013 2:42\n# \"Passion and Pain Taste the Same When I'm Weak\" \u2013 4:00\n\n== Charts ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2020)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| New Zealand Hot Singles ([[Recorded Music NZ|RMNZ]])<ref name=\"nz\"></ref>\n| 35\n|-\n{{single chart|Sweden|76|artist=Tove Lo|song=Bikini Porn|rowheader=true|accessdate=23 February 2020|refname=swe}}\n|}\n\n== Credits and personnel ==\nCredits adapted from [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]].<ref name=\"tidal\">{{cite web | url=https://listen.tidal.com/album/127615666/credits | title=Bikini Porn, credits | publisher=[[Tidal (service)|Tidal]] | accessdate=29 February 2020 | archive-url=http://archive.is/2cg1f | archive-date=29 February 2020}}</ref>\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n:For \"Bikini Porn\":\n* [[Lead vocals]], [[background vocals]]&nbsp;\u2013 Tove Lo\n* [[Songwriter|Songwriting]]