{"title_page": "V\u00e1clav Kopeck\u00fd", "text_new": "{{short description|Czechoslovak member of Czechoslovak national parliament and Czechoslovak politician}}\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 183-30268-0001, Friedensfahrt, Vaclav Kopecky (cropped).jpg|thumb|Kopeck\u00fd in [[East Germany]], 1955]]\n\n'''V\u00e1clav Kopeck\u00fd''' (27 August 1897 in [[Kosmonosy]]&nbsp;\u2013 5 August 1961 in [[Prague]])<ref name=\"Churan\" /> was a [[Communist Party of Czechoslovakia|Czechoslovak Communist]] politician. A member of the party since the interwar era, he spent World War II in Moscow and served as minister of culture and information in the postwar government. Kopeck\u00fd was noted for his antisemitic statements, criticizing Jews for [[Zionism]] and [[rootless cosmopolitanism|cosmopolitanism]]; he also stage-managed the [[Sl\u00e1nsk\u00fd trial]], an antisemitic [[show trial]].\n\n==Early career==\nHe had a proletarian upringing as the thirteenth child of a small tradesman and [[Sokol]] official.<ref name=Churan>{{cite book |last1=Chura\u0148 |first1=Milan |title=Kdo byl kdo v na\u0161ich d\u011bjin\u00e1ch ve 20. stolet\u00ed |date=1998 |publisher=Nakl. Libri |isbn=978-80-85983-44-9 |page=340 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=ICDvAAAAMAAJ&q=V%C3%A1clav+Kopeck%C3%BD&dq=V%C3%A1clav+Kopeck%C3%BD |language=cs}}</ref> In the interwar period, Kopeck\u00fd was a member of the underground Karl\u00edn communist cell along with future party leaders [[Klement Gottwald]] and [[Rudolf Sl\u00e1nsk\u00fd]].<ref name=Wein>{{cite book |last1=Wein |first1=Martin |title=A History of Czechs and Jews: A Slavic Jerusalem |date=2015 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-317-60821-9 |pages=97, 156, 158 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=0bugBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA158&lpg=PA158&dq=Kopeck%C3%BD+Slansky#v=onepage&q=Kopeck%C3%BD%20Slansky&f=false |language=en}}</ref> From 1940 to 1941, Kopeck\u00fd was a representative of the [[Comintern]],<ref>{{cite book |last1=Rees |first1=Tim |last2=Thorpe |first2=Andrew |title=International Communism and the Communist International, 1919-43 |date=1998 |publisher=Manchester University Press |isbn=978-0-7190-5546-1 |page=54 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dttCVcOvmdcC&q=Kopecky#v=snippet&q=Kopecky&f=false |language=en}}</ref> spending World War II in the Soviet Union.<ref name=KL>{{cite book |last1=Kub\u00e1tov\u00e1 |first1=Hana |last2=L\u00e1n\u00ed\u010dek |first2=Jan |authorlink2=Jan L\u00e1n\u00ed\u010dek |title=The Jew in Czech and Slovak Imagination, 1938-89: Antisemitism, the Holocaust, and Zionism |date=2018 |publisher=Brill |location=Leiden |isbn=978-90-04-36244-4 |page=178 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=7HtTDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA178&dq=V%C3%A1clav+Kopeck%C3%BD#v=onepage&q=V%C3%A1clav%20Kopeck%C3%BD&f=false |language=en}}</ref> In July 1944, he voiced the sentiments of the emerging Communist consensus on postwar nationality issues, which rejected [[Communist internationalism]] and accepted the [[Czechoslovak government-in-exile]]'s plans for national homogenization via the [[expulsion of Sudeten Germans]]. Expressing hope that the [[Jewish question]] would \"forever disappear... as a decoy for reactionary elements\",<ref name=\"KL\" /> Kopeck\u00fd declared:\n{{quote|Those Jews who feel themselves to be Germans or Hungarians must face the same measures that will be taken against the Germans and Hungarians in Czechoslovakia. The liquidation of anti-Semitism does not mean that we will grant the Jews special privileges if they feel themselves to be Germans or Hungarians. Nor will we allow those who feel themselves to be Germans and Hungarians to hide their true feelings behind the claim of Jewishness. Liquidation of anti-Semitism cannot be allowed to cause harm to the national and Slavic character of the future Czechoslovak Republic.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Cichopek |first1=Anna |title=Beyond Violence: Jewish Survivors in Poland and Slovakia, 1944\u201348|title-link=Beyond Violence: Jewish Survivors in Poland and Slovakia, 1944\u201348 |date=2014 |location=Cambridge |publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-107-03666-6 |ref=harv |language=en|p=165}}</ref>}}\n\n==Minister==\n{{see also|Anti-cosmopolitan campaign}}\nHe served as the Minister of Culture and Information in the postwar Czechoslovak government.<ref name=\"Cinema\">{{cite book |last1=Karl |first1=Lars |last2=Skopal |first2=Pavel |title=Cinema in Service of the State: Perspectives on Film Culture in the GDR and Czechoslovakia, 1945-1960 |date=2015 |publisher=Berghahn Books |isbn=978-1-78238-997-2 |page=44 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=chHJCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA54&dq=V%C3%A1clav+Kopeck%C3%BD#v=onepage&q=V%C3%A1clav%20Kopeck%C3%BD&f=false |language=en}}</ref><ref name=books>{{cite book |last1=\u0160mejkalov\u00e1 |first1=Ji\u0159ina |title=Cold War Books in the 'Other' Europe and What Came After |date=2010 |publisher=Brill |location=Leiden |isbn=978-90-04-19357-4 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=EOF5DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA147&dq=V%C3%A1clav+Kopeck%C3%BD#v=onepage&q=V%C3%A1clav%20Kopeck%C3%BD&f=false |language=en|pp=138, 147}}</ref> As Minister of Information, Kopeck\u00fd surrounded himself with Communist sympathizing artists. Czech poet [[Franti\u0161ek Halas]] led the ministry's publishing department; writer [[Ivan Olbracht]] headed the radio department; visual artist {{ill|Adolf Hoffmeister|cs||de}} the foreign affairs department; and a film department by [[V\u00edt\u011bzslav Nezval]].<ref name=\"Cinema\" /> Under Kopeck\u00fd's leadership, the Ministry of Information adapted the Nazi government's management of book publication under the guise of needing to replace the books destroyed during the Nazi occupation. Publishers had to submit their books to the publishing department of the Ministry of Information half a year in advance for review. This process did not initially involve ideological censorship and was aimed at freeing writers from the demands of the free market.<ref name=\"books\" /> After the [[death of Jan Masaryk]], Kopeck\u00fd instructed the media not to mention Masaryk's name.<ref>{{cite news |title=F\u00fcnf m\u00e4nner kamen nach mitternacht |url=https://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-46272168.html |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=Der Spiegel |issue=15 |date=1965}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Czech historian Michal Frankl, Kopeck\u00fd \"distinguished himself with antisemitic diatribes\", criticizing the presence of Jews in politics and attacking [[Zionism]] and [[rootless cosmopolitans|cosmopolitanism]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Sl\u00e1nsk\u00fd Trial |url=https://yivoencyclopedia.org/article.aspx/Slansky_Trial |website=[[YIVO Encyclopedia]]|last=Frankl|first=Michal |accessdate=16 March 2020|date=2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Meyer |first1=Peter |title=The Jewish Purge in the Satellite Countries: Behind the Communist Turn to Anti-Semitism |url=https://www.commentarymagazine.com/articles/peter-meyer/the-jewish-purge-in-the-satellite-countriesbehind-the-communist-turn-to-anti-semitism/ |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=Commentary |date=1 September 1952}}</ref> In 1945, he accused the \"Jewish super-rich like [[Petschek]], Weinmann, [[Rothschild family|Rothschild]], Gutman\" of \"blood-sucking\" and argued that wealthy Jews could not live in the [[People's democracy (Marxism\u2013Leninism)|people's democracy]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Pynsent |first1=Robert B. |authorlink=:cs:Robert Pynsent|title=Conclusory Essay: Activists, Jews, The Little Czech Man, and Germans |url=http://discovery.ucl.ac.uk/13018/1/13018.pdf|journal=Central Europe |date=18 July 2013 |volume=5 |issue=2 |pages=326 |doi=10.1179/174582107x190906|ref=harv}}</ref> He also objected to the resettlement of Jews from [[Carpathian Ruthenia]] in postwar Czechoslovakia.<ref>{{cite news |title=Czech Minister Denies Anti-semitism, but Repeats Charges Against Carpathian Jews |url=https://www.jta.org/1947/04/03/archive/czech-minister-denies-anti-semitism-but-repeats-cparges-against-carpathian-jews |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=Jewish Telegraphic Agency |date=3 April 1947}}</ref> For Rudolf Sl\u00e1nsk\u00fd's fiftieth birthday in July 1951, Kopeck\u00fd lauded him in the party newspaper ''[[Rud\u00e9 pr\u00e1vo]]'' and claimed that \"already at home and at primary school [Sl\u00e1nsk\u00fd] absorbed a full-blooded native Czechness\".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=\u0160imov\u00e1 |first1=Kate\u0159ina |title=The image of the \u201cJew\u201d as an \u201cenemy\u201d in the propaganda of Late Stalinism and its reflection in the Czechoslovak context |journal=Holocaust Studies |date=10 August 2016 |page=128 |doi=10.1080/17504902.2016.1209840}}</ref> Despite their former association, Kopeck\u00fd became a personal enemy of Sl\u00e1nsk\u00fd and was involved in the [[Sl\u00e1nsk\u00fd trial]] as one of the main stage managers of the [[show trial]].<ref name=\"Wein\" /> In December 1951, he complained that many of the alleged conspirators \"come from wealthy Jewish families\" and that \"the great part of people with a Jewish origin\" subscribe to \"cosmopolitan thinking\".<ref name=\"Wein\" /> According to Kopeck\u00fd, this demonstrated that the party was not taking the anti-cosmopolitan campaign seriously enough and was underestimating the \"very serious danger\" posed by Zionism.<ref name=\"Wein\" /> Historian [[Karel Kaplan]] described Kopeck\u00fd as \"the party ideologue of show trials\".<ref>{{cite book |last1=Kaplan |first1=Karel |title=Report on the murder of the General Secretary |date=1990 |publisher=Ohio State University Press |isbn=978-0-8142-0477-1 |page=149 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a1qvAAAAIAAJ&q=V%C3%A1clav+Kopeck%C3%BD+cosmopolitans&dq=V%C3%A1clav+Kopeck%C3%BD+cosmopolitans&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjjn67d29noAhUHrp4KHRCZCEk4ChDoATABegQIBRAC |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite thesis|last=P\u00e1vov\u00e1|first=Jana|title=V\u00e1clav Kopeck\u00fd (1897-1961) - portr\u00e9t komunistick\u00e9ho politika|url=https://dspace.cuni.cz/handle/20.500.11956/19368 |date=2008|degree= Rigor\u00f3zn\u00ed pr\u00e1ce. |institution=Univerzita Karlova, Filozofick\u00e1 fakulta, \u00dastav \u010desk\u00fdch d\u011bjin|editor-last= Rychl\u00edk|editor-first= Jan}}\n\n{{Government of Czechoslovakia (1946\u20131948)}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kopecky, Vaclav}}\n[[Category:1897 births]]\n[[Category:1961 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Kosmonosy]]\n[[Category:People from the Kingdom of Bohemia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Central Committee of the Communist Party of Czechoslovakia]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Czechoslovakia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Chamber of Deputies of Czechoslovakia (1929\u20131935)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Chamber of Deputies of Czechoslovakia (1935\u20131939)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Interim National Assembly of Czechoslovakia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Constituent National Assembly of Czechoslovakia]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly of Czechoslovakia (1948\u20131954)]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly of Czechoslovakia (1954\u20131960)]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly of Czechoslovakia (1960\u20131964)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Czechoslovak member of Czechoslovak national parliament and Czechoslovak politician}}\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 183-30268-0001, Friedensfahrt, Vaclav Kopecky (cropped).jpg|thumb|Kopeck\u00fd in [[East Germany]], 1955]]\n\n'''V\u00e1clav Kopeck\u00fd''' (27 August 1897 in [[Kosmonosy]] \u2013 5 August 1961 in [[Prague]])<ref name=\"Churan\" /> was a [[Communist Party of Czechoslovakia|Czechoslovak Communist]] politician. A member of the party since the interwar era, he spent World War II in Moscow and served as minister of culture and information in the postwar government. Kopeck\u00fd was noted for his antisemitic statements, criticizing Jews for [[Zionism]] and [[rootless cosmopolitanism|cosmopolitanism]]; he also stage-managed the [[Sl\u00e1nsk\u00fd trial]], an antisemitic [[show trial]].\n\n==Early career==\nHe had a proletarian upringing as the thirteenth child of a small tradesman and [[Sokol]] official.<ref name=Churan>{{cite book |last1=Chura\u0148 |first1=Milan |title=Kdo byl kdo v na\u0161ich d\u011bjin\u00e1ch ve 20. stolet\u00ed |date=1998 |publisher=Nakl. Libri |isbn=978-80-85983-44-9 |page=340 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=ICDvAAAAMAAJ&q=V%C3%A1clav+Kopeck%C3%BD&dq=V%C3%A1clav+Kopeck%C3%BD |language=cs}}</ref> In the interwar period, Kopeck\u00fd was a member of the underground Karl\u00edn communist cell along with future party leaders [[Klement Gottwald]] and [[Rudolf Sl\u00e1nsk\u00fd]].<ref name=Wein>{{cite book |last1=Wein |first1=Martin |title=A History of Czechs and Jews: A Slavic Jerusalem |date=2015 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-317-60821-9 |pages=97, 156, 158 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=0bugBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA158&lpg=PA158&dq=Kopeck%C3%BD+Slansky#v=onepage&q=Kopeck%C3%BD%20Slansky&f=false |language=en}}</ref> From 1940 to 1941, Kopeck\u00fd was a representative of the [[Comintern]],<ref>{{cite book |last1=Rees |first1=Tim |last2=Thorpe |first2=Andrew |title=International Communism and the Communist International, 1919-43 |date=1998 |publisher=Manchester University Press |isbn=978-0-7190-5546-1 |page=54 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dttCVcOvmdcC&q=Kopecky#v=snippet&q=Kopecky&f=false |language=en}}</ref> spending World War II in the Soviet Union.<ref name=KL>{{cite book |last1=Kub\u00e1tov\u00e1 |first1=Hana |last2=L\u00e1n\u00ed\u010dek |first2=Jan |authorlink2=Jan L\u00e1n\u00ed\u010dek |title=The Jew in Czech and Slovak Imagination, 1938-89: Antisemitism, the Holocaust, and Zionism |date=2018 |publisher=Brill |location=Leiden |isbn=978-90-04-36244-4 |page=178 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=7HtTDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA178&dq=V%C3%A1clav+Kopeck%C3%BD#v=onepage&q=V%C3%A1clav%20Kopeck%C3%BD&f=false |language=en}}</ref> In July 1944, he voiced the sentiments of the emerging Communist consensus on postwar nationality issues, which rejected [[Communist internationalism]] and accepted the [[Czechoslovak government-in-exile]]'s plans for national homogenization via the [[expulsion of Sudeten Germans]]. Expressing hope that the [[Jewish question]] would \"forever disappear... as a decoy for reactionary elements\",<ref name=\"KL\" /> Kopeck\u00fd declared:\n{{quote|Those Jews who feel themselves to be Germans or Hungarians must face the same measures that will be taken against the Germans and Hungarians in Czechoslovakia. The liquidation of anti-Semitism does not mean that we will grant the Jews special privileges if they feel themselves to be Germans or Hungarians. Nor will we allow those who feel themselves to be Germans and Hungarians to hide their true feelings behind the claim of Jewishness. Liquidation of anti-Semitism cannot be allowed to cause harm to the national and Slavic character of the future Czechoslovak Republic.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Cichopek |first1=Anna |title=Beyond Violence: Jewish Survivors in Poland and Slovakia, 1944\u201348|title-link=Beyond Violence: Jewish Survivors in Poland and Slovakia, 1944\u201348 |date=2014 |location=Cambridge |publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-107-03666-6 |ref=harv |language=en|p=165}}</ref>}}\n\n==Minister==\n{{see also|Anti-cosmopolitan campaign}}\nHe served as the Minister of Culture and Information in the postwar Czechoslovak government.<ref name=\"Cinema\">{{cite book |last1=Karl |first1=Lars |last2=Skopal |first2=Pavel |title=Cinema in Service of the State: Perspectives on Film Culture in the GDR and Czechoslovakia, 1945-1960 |date=2015 |publisher=Berghahn Books |isbn=978-1-78238-997-2 |page=44 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=chHJCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA54&dq=V%C3%A1clav+Kopeck%C3%BD#v=onepage&q=V%C3%A1clav%20Kopeck%C3%BD&f=false |language=en}}</ref><ref name=books>{{cite book |last1=\u0160mejkalov\u00e1 |first1=Ji\u0159ina |title=Cold War Books in the 'Other' Europe and What Came After |date=2010 |publisher=Brill |location=Leiden |isbn=978-90-04-19357-4 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=EOF5DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA147&dq=V%C3%A1clav+Kopeck%C3%BD#v=onepage&q=V%C3%A1clav%20Kopeck%C3%BD&f=false |language=en|pp=138, 147}}</ref> As Minister of Information, Kopeck\u00fd surrounded himself with Communist sympathizing artists. Czech poet [[Franti\u0161ek Halas]] led the ministry's publishing department; writer [[Ivan Olbracht]] headed the radio department; visual artist {{ill|Adolf Hoffmeister|cs||de}} the foreign affairs department; and a film department by [[V\u00edt\u011bzslav Nezval]].<ref name=\"Cinema\" /> Under Kopeck\u00fd's leadership, the Ministry of Information adapted the Nazi government's management of book publication under the guise of needing to replace the books destroyed during the Nazi occupation. Publishers had to submit their books to the publishing department of the Ministry of Information half a year in advance for review. This process did not initially involve ideological censorship and was aimed at freeing writers from the demands of the free market.<ref name=\"books\" />  After the [[death of Jan Masaryk]], Kopeck\u00fd instructed the media not to mention Masaryk's name.<ref>{{cite news |title=F\u00fcnf m\u00e4nner kamen nach mitternacht |url=https://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-46272168.html |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=Der Spiegel |issue=15 |date=1965}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Czech historian Michal Frankl, Kopeck\u00fd \"distinguished himself with antisemitic diatribes\", criticizing the presence of Jews in politics and attacking [[Zionism]] and [[rootless cosmopolitans|cosmopolitanism]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Sl\u00e1nsk\u00fd Trial |url=https://yivoencyclopedia.org/article.aspx/Slansky_Trial |website=[[YIVO Encyclopedia]]|last=Frankl|first=Michal |accessdate=16 March 2020|date=2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Meyer |first1=Peter |title=The Jewish Purge in the Satellite Countries: Behind the Communist Turn to Anti-Semitism |url=https://www.commentarymagazine.com/articles/peter-meyer/the-jewish-purge-in-the-satellite-countriesbehind-the-communist-turn-to-anti-semitism/ |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=Commentary |date=1 September 1952}}</ref> In 1945, he accused the \"Jewish super-rich like [[Petschek]], Weinmann, [[Rothschild family|Rothschild]], Gutman\" of \"blood-sucking\" and argued that wealthy Jews could not live in the [[People's democracy (Marxism\u2013Leninism)|people's democracy]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Pynsent |first1=Robert B. |authorlink=:cs:Robert Pynsent|title=Conclusory Essay: Activists, Jews, The Little Czech Man, and Germans |url=http://discovery.ucl.ac.uk/13018/1/13018.pdf|journal=Central Europe |date=18 July 2013 |volume=5 |issue=2 |pages=326 |doi=10.1179/174582107x190906|ref=harv}}</ref> He also objected to the resettlement of Jews from [[Carpathian Ruthenia]] in postwar Czechoslovakia.<ref>{{cite news |title=Czech Minister Denies Anti-semitism, but Repeats Charges Against Carpathian Jews |url=https://www.jta.org/1947/04/03/archive/czech-minister-denies-anti-semitism-but-repeats-cparges-against-carpathian-jews |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=Jewish Telegraphic Agency |date=3 April 1947}}</ref> For Rudolf Sl\u00e1nsk\u00fd's fiftieth birthday in July 1951, Kopeck\u00fd lauded him in the party newspaper ''[[Rud\u00e9 pr\u00e1vo]]'' and claimed that \"already at home and at primary school [Sl\u00e1nsk\u00fd] absorbed a full-blooded native Czechness\".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=\u0160imov\u00e1 |first1=Kate\u0159ina |title=The image of the \u201cJew\u201d as an \u201cenemy\u201d in the propaganda of Late Stalinism and its reflection in the Czechoslovak context |journal=Holocaust Studies |date=10 August 2016 |page=128 |doi=10.1080/17504902.2016.1209840}}</ref> Despite their former association, Kopeck\u00fd became a personal enemy of Sl\u00e1nsk\u00fd and was involved in the [[Sl\u00e1nsk\u00fd trial]] as one of the main stage managers of the [[show trial]].<ref name=\"Wein\" /> In December 1951, he complained that many of the alleged conspirators \"come from wealthy Jewish families\" and that \"the great part of people with a Jewish origin\" subscribe to \"cosmopolitan thinking\".<ref name=\"Wein\" /> According to Kopeck\u00fd,  this demonstrated that the party was not taking the anti-cosmopolitan campaign seriously enough and was underestimating the \"very serious danger\" posed by Zionism.<ref name=\"Wein\" /> Historian [[Karel Kaplan]] described Kopeck\u00fd as \"the party ideologue of show trials\".<ref>{{cite book |last1=Kaplan |first1=Karel |title=Report on the murder of the General Secretary |date=1990 |publisher=Ohio State University Press |isbn=978-0-8142-0477-1 |page=149 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a1qvAAAAIAAJ&q=V%C3%A1clav+Kopeck%C3%BD+cosmopolitans&dq=V%C3%A1clav+Kopeck%C3%BD+cosmopolitans&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjjn67d29noAhUHrp4KHRCZCEk4ChDoATABegQIBRAC |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite thesis|last=P\u00e1vov\u00e1|first=Jana|title=V\u00e1clav Kopeck\u00fd (1897-1961) - portr\u00e9t komunistick\u00e9ho politika|url=https://dspace.cuni.cz/handle/20.500.11956/19368 |date=2008|degree= Rigor\u00f3zn\u00ed pr\u00e1ce. |institution=Univerzita Karlova, Filozofick\u00e1 fakulta, \u00dastav \u010desk\u00fdch d\u011bjin|editor-last= Rychl\u00edk|editor-first= Jan}}\n\n{{Government of Czechoslovakia (1946\u20131948)}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kopecky, Vaclav}}\n[[Category:1897 births]]\n[[Category:1961 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Kosmonosy]]\n[[Category:People from the Kingdom of Bohemia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Central Committee of the Communist Party of Czechoslovakia]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Czechoslovakia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Chamber of Deputies of Czechoslovakia (1929\u20131935)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Chamber of Deputies of Czechoslovakia (1935\u20131939)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Interim National Assembly of Czechoslovakia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Constituent National Assembly of Czechoslovakia]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly of Czechoslovakia (1948\u20131954)]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly of Czechoslovakia (1954\u20131960)]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly of Czechoslovakia (1960\u20131964)]]\n", "name_user": "JHunterJ", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/V%C3%A1clav_Kopeck%C3%BD"}
{"title_page": "Nucleocytoplasmic large DNA viruses", "text_new": "{{Taxobox\n| color=violet\n| name = ''Megavirales''\n| image =\n| image_caption =\n| virus_group = i\n| subdivision_ranks = Families{{cn|date=October 2019}}\n| subdivision = \n''[[Ascoviridae]]''<br/>\n''[[Asfarviridae]]''<br/>\n''[[Iridoviridae]]''<br/>\n''[[Marseilleviridae]]''<br/>\n''[[Megaviridae]]'' (syn. ''Mimiviridae'')<br/>\n''[[Pandoraviridae]]''<br/>\n''[[Phycodnaviridae]]''<br/>\n''[[Pithoviridae]]'' <br>\n''[[Poxviridae]]''\n}}\n\nThe '''nucleocytoplasmic large DNA viruses''' '''(NCLDV)''' are a proposed order of [[DNA_virus#Group_I:_dsDNA_viruses|dsDNA]] [[virus]]es, notable for containing the '''''Megavirales''''' or [[giant virus]]es.<ref name=\"Colson2012\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Colson P, de Lamballerie X, Fournous G, Raoult D |year=2012 |title=Reclassification of giant viruses composing a fourth domain of life in the new order Megavirales|journal=Intervirology |volume=55 |issue=5 |pages=321\u2013332 |doi=10.1159/000336562 |pmid=22508375}}</ref><ref name=\"Colson2013\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Colson P, De Lamballerie X, Yutin N, Asgari S, Bigot Y, Bideshi DK, Cheng XW, Federici BA, Van Etten JL, Koonin EV, La Scola B, Raoult D |year=2013 |title=\"Megavirales\", a proposed new order for eukaryotic nucleocytoplasmic large DNA viruses |journal=Arch Virol |volume=158 |issue=12 |pages=2517\u201321 |doi=10.1007/s00705-013-1768-6 |pmid=23812617 |pmc=4066373}}</ref> There are nine families of NCLDVs that all share certain genomic and structural characteristics; however, it is uncertain whether the similarities of the different families of this group have a common viral ancestor.<ref name=\"Iyer2001\">{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1128/JVI.75.23.11720-11734.2001 | volume = 75| issue = 23| pages = 11720\u201334| date = December 2001| last1 = Iyer | first1 = L. M.| last2 = Aravind | first2 = L.| last3 = Koonin | first3 = E. V. | pmid=11689653 | pmc=114758 | title=Common Origin of Four Diverse Families of Large Eukaryotic DNA Viruses | journal = Journal of Virology }}</ref> One feature of this group is a large [[genome]] and the presence of many [[gene]]s involved in [[DNA repair]], [[DNA replication]], [[transcription (biology)|transcription]], and [[translation]]. Typically, viruses with smaller genomes do not contain genes for these processes. Most of the viruses in this family also replicate in both the host's [[cell nucleus|nucleus]] and [[cytoplasm]], thus the name nucleocytoplasmic.\n\nThere are 47 NCLDV core genes currently recognised. These include four key proteins involved in DNA replication and repair: the [[enzyme]]s [[DNA polymerase]] family B, the [[topoisomerase]] II A, the [[5-lipoxygenase-activating protein|FLAP]] [[endonuclease]] and the processing factor [[proliferating cell nuclear antigen]]. Other proteins include DNA dependent [[RNA polymerase]] II and [[transcription factor]] II B.\n\n==''Ascoviridae''==\nMembers of the family ''[[Ascoviridae]]'' come in different shapes. Some can be rod-shaped, while others are oval. They measure up to 130&nbsp;nm wide and 400&nbsp;nm long. Theses viruses have circular double stranded DNA that have a length of about 100\u2013200 kilobase pairs. They infect lepidopteran insect larvae and can infect through parasitoid wasps. Once they infect they replicate and cause death in insect pest. This allows them to control insect populations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://talk.ictvonline.org/ictv-reports/ictv_online_report/dsdna-viruses/w/ascoviridae#Citation|title=Ascoviridae\u2014Ascoviridae\u2014dsDNA Viruses\u2014International Committee on Taxonomy of Viruses (ICTV)|website=International Committee on Taxonomy of Viruses (ICTV)|language=en|access-date=2017-12-07}}</ref> Ascoviridae can have up to 180 genes in its genome. The replication of this virus takes place in the nucleus of the host cell. When it replicates, it causes the nucleus to increase in size and eventually burst. After, the virion starts to form and spread.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Asgari|first=Sassan|last2=Bideshi|first2=Dennis K|last3=Bigot|first3=Yves|last4=Federici|first4=Brian A|last5=Cheng|first5=Xiao-Wen|year=2017|title=ICTV Virus Taxonomy Profile: Ascoviridae|journal=The Journal of General Virology|volume=98|issue=1|pages=4\u20135|doi=10.1099/jgv.0.000677|issn=0022-1317|pmc=5370392|pmid=28218573}}</ref>\n\n==''Asfarviridae''==\nA member of the family ''[[Asfarviridae]]'' is a known as an asfarvirus. This virus is the cause of African swine fever. Some of the symptoms for this flu include fever, high pulse, fast breathing, and it can cause death. These symptoms can be similar to those from hog cholera, the difference is that the African swine flu can not be cured. There is no vaccine developed to fight this virus.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.britannica.com/science/African-swine-fever|title=African swine fever (ASF) {{!}} animal disease|encyclopedia=Encyclopedia Britannica|access-date=2017-12-07|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==''Iridoviridae''==\nThe ''[[Iridoviridae]]'' have linear double stranded DNA genomes up to 220 kilobases long and can code for about 211 proteins. The capsid of this virion is icosahedral shaped and can be up to 350&nbsp;nm wide. The replication cycle of this virus begins in the nucleus of the host and end in the cytoplasm. Some viruses of this family are often found infecting amphibians while other are found in insect and crustaceans.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://talk.ictvonline.org/ictv-reports/ictv_online_report/dsdna-viruses/w/iridoviridae|title=Iridoviridae\u2014Iridoviridae\u2014dsDNA Viruses\u2014International Committee on Taxonomy of Viruses (ICTV)|website=International Committee on Taxonomy of Viruses (ICTV)|language=en|access-date=2017-12-07}}</ref>\n\n==''Marseilleviridae''==\nThe ''[[Marseilleviridae]]'' viruses have double stranded DNA genomes that are about 372 kilobases long. Members of the family can have about 457 [[open reading frame]]s (ORFs) in its genome. The host organisms are [[amoeba]]e. Once it infects, viral replication takes place in the cytoplasm.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}} It was found that the genome of the family ''Marseilleviridae'' codes for about 28 different proteins.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Boyer|first=Micka\u00ebl|last2=Yutin|first2=Natalya|last3=Pagnier|first3=Isabelle|last4=Barrassi|first4=Lina|last5=Fournous|first5=Ghislain|last6=Espinosa|first6=Leon|last7=Robert|first7=Catherine|last8=Azza|first8=Sa\u00efd|last9=Sun|first9=Siyang|date=2009-12-22|title=Giant Marseillevirus highlights the role of amoebae as a melting pot in emergence of chimeric microorganisms|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America|volume=106|issue=51|pages=21848\u201321853|doi=10.1073/pnas.0911354106|issn=0027-8424|pmc=2799887|pmid=20007369|bibcode=2009PNAS..10621848B}}</ref>&nbsp;The capsid of the marseillevirus is about 250&nbsp;nm wide with a geometry shape of an icosahedral. The replication of this virus usually occurs near the nucleus once it infects the amoeba. Once the virus infects it can cause a shape change in the host\u2019s nucleus.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2014-10-01|title=The expanding family Marseilleviridae|journal=Virology|volume=466\u2013467|pages=27\u201337|doi=10.1016/j.virol.2014.07.014|pmid=25104553|issn=0042-6822 | last1 = Aherfi | first1 = Sarah}}</ref>\n\n==''Megaviridae''==\nThe ''[[Megaviridae]]'' contains some of the largest viruses ever discovered. They have linear double stranded DNA genomes with the length of 1,259,197 base pairs, which is larger than some small bacteria. Within in this genome 1,100 proteins are coded. 74.76% of the base pairs are represented by thymine and adenine. The ''Megaviridae'' virus can be found infecting acanthamoeba or other protozoan clades. &nbsp;Once the virus infects the host, the replication cycle takes place in the cytoplasm. Within the genome, DNA repair enzymes can be found. These are used when the DNA is harmed such as when it is exposed to ionizing radiation or UV light.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Arslan|first=Defne|last2=Legendre|first2=Matthieu|last3=Seltzer|first3=Virginie|last4=Abergel|first4=Chantal|last5=Claverie|first5=Jean-Michel|date=2011-10-18|title=Distant Mimivirus relative with a larger genome highlights the fundamental features of Megaviridae|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|language=en|volume=108|issue=42|pages=17486\u201317491|doi=10.1073/pnas.1110889108|issn=0027-8424|pmid=21987820|pmc=3198346|bibcode=2011PNAS..10817486A}}</ref>\n\nTraditionally these viruses have been grouped into a family ''Mimiviridae''. Later it appeared that the viruses of the ''Organic Lake Phycodna Group'' (OLPG) are more related to Mimiviruses than to [[Phycodnaviridae|Phycodnaviruses]]. For this reason it has been proposed adding them to legacy Mimiviridae as new subfamily ''Mesomimivirinae'' in order to form the more comprehensive family ''Megaviridae''. However, the term ''Mimiviridae'' nowadays is used ''sensu lato'' synonymous with ''Megaviridae''.<ref name=Schulz2017>{{Cite journal|last=Schulz|first=Frederik|last2=Yutin|first2=Natalya|last3=Ivanova|first3=Natalia N.|last4=Ortega|first4=Davi R.|last5=Lee|first5=Tae Kwon|last6=Vierheilig|first6=Julia|last7=Daims|first7=Holger|last8=Horn|first8=Matthias|last9=Wagner|first9=Michael|date=2017-04-07|title=Giant viruses with an expanded complement of translation system components|journal=Science|language=en|volume=356|issue=6333|pages=82\u201385|doi=10.1126/science.aal4657|pmid=28386012|issn=0036-8075|bibcode=2017Sci...356...82S|url=https://cloudfront.escholarship.org/dist/prd/content/qt0kf9t6gn/qt0kf9t6gn.pdf}}, UCPMS ID: 1889607, [http://escholarship.org/uc/item/0kf9t6gn.pdf PDF]</ref><ref>Eugene V Koonin, Mart Krupovic, Natalya Yutin: [https://www.researchgate.net/publication/272946690_Evolution_of_double-stranded_DNA_viruses_of_eukaryotes_From_bacteriophages_to_transposons_to_giant_viruses Evolution of double-stranded DNA viruses of eukaryotes: From bacteriophages to transposons to giant viruses], in: ResearchGate Literature Review February 2015, [[doi: 10.1111/nyas.12728]], Figure 3</ref><ref>Natalya Yutin et al.: [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3620924/ Mimiviridae: clusters of orthologous genes, reconstruction of gene repertoire evolution and proposed expansion of the giant virus family], in: Virol J. 2013; 10: 106, [[doi: 10.1186/1743-422X-10-106]]</ref><ref>Blog of Carolina Reyes, Kenneth Stedman: [https://www.researchgate.net/post/Are_Phaeocystis_globosa_viruses_OLPG_and_Organic_Lake_phycodnavirus_a_part_of_the_Phycodnaviridae_or_Mimiviridae Are Phaeocystis globosa viruses (OLPG) and Organic Lake phycodnavirus a part of the Phycodnaviridae or Mimiviridae?], on ResearchGate, Jan. 8, 2016</ref><ref>Fumito Maruyama and Shoko Ueki: [http://journal.frontiersin.org/article/10.3389/fmicb.2016.01942/full Evolution and Phylogeny of Large DNA Viruses, ''Mimiviridae'' and ''Phycodnaviridae'' Including Newly Characterized ''Heterosigma akashiwo Virus''], in: Front. Microbiol., 30 November 2016, [[doi: 10.3389/fmicb.2016.01942]]</ref><ref name=\"WZhang\">Weijia Zhang et al.:  [https://www.nature.com/articles/srep15131 Four novel algal virus genomes discovered from Yellowstone Lake metagenomes], in: Scientific Reports 5, Article number: 15131 (2015), especially Figure 6, [[doi: 10.1038/srep15131]]</ref> \n\n==''Pandoraviridae''==\n''[[Pandoravirus|Pandoraviridae]]'' Discovered in 2013 from a coastal water sample in Chile. It is mostly found infecting amoebae. It has a length of 1 micrometer long and .5 micrometer wide. Its genome can be up to 2.5 million base pairs long.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yong|first=Ed|title=Giant viruses open Pandora's box|url=https://www.nature.com/news/giant-viruses-open-pandora-s-box-1.13410|journal=Nature|language=en|doi=10.1038/nature.2013.13410|year=2013}}</ref> The replication of this virus take place in the cytoplasm. Like other giant viruses, it affect the host\u2019s nucleus and can take up to 15 hours to start infecting.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Aherfi|first=Sarah|last2=Colson|first2=Philippe|last3=La Scola|first3=Bernard|last4=Raoult|first4=Didier|date=2016-03-22|title=Giant Viruses of Amoebas: An Update|journal=Frontiers in Microbiology|volume=7|pages=349|doi=10.3389/fmicb.2016.00349|issn=1664-302X|pmc=4801854|pmid=27047465}}</ref> Although it is found in water, it does not affect humans, it may actually help us by increasing the production of oxygen in aquatic environments.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2013/07/130718-viruses-pandoraviruses-science-biology-evolution/|title=Biggest Virus Yet Found, May Be Fourth Domain of Life?|date=2013-07-19|access-date=2017-12-07}}</ref>'''&nbsp;'''\n\n==''Phycodnaviridae''==\nThe ''[[Phycodnaviridae]]'' are icosahedral in shape with a double-stranded DNA molecule. Some members of this family can have a linear double stranded DNA while others have a circular double stranded DNA. The genome has been found to be up to 560 kilobases in length. Up to 50% of the DNA can be represented by guanine or cytosine. This virus is known to infect algae, which means it is found in the ocean.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Wilson|first=W. H.|last2=Van Etten|first2=J. L.|last3=Allen|first3=M. J.|date=2009|title=The Phycodnaviridae: The Story of How Tiny Giants Rule the World|volume=328|pages=1\u201342|issn=0070-217X|pmc=2908299|pmid=19216434|doi=10.1007/978-3-540-68618-7_1|series=Current Topics in Microbiology and Immunology|isbn=978-3-540-68617-0}}</ref>\n\n==''Pithoviridae''==\nThe ''[[Pithovirus|Pithoviridae]]'' have only two known representatives. These viruses infects amoebas and can survive in low temperatures. For years this virus was believed to be frozen, but due to climate change it has begun to show up again.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sciencenewsforstudents.org/article/return-giant-zombie-virus|title=Return of the giant zombie virus|last=Ornes|first=Stephen|date=2017-07-31|work=Science News for Students|access-date=2017-12-07|language=en}}</ref>&nbsp;This is a double stranded DNA virus with its size being 610 kilobases long. The genome is estimated to code for 476 open reading frames. The viron is rod shaped with a length of 1,100&nbsp;nm long and 500&nbsp;nm in diameter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://viralzone.expasy.org/4237?outline=all_by_species|title=Pithovirus|website=viralzone.expasy.org|access-date=2017-12-07}}</ref>\n\n==''Poxviridae''==\nThe ''[[Poxviridae]]'' have a linear double-stranded DNA molecule that can have a length of up to 230 kilobases. The replication of these viruses takes place in the cytoplasm. [[Smallpox]], [[cowpox]], and other [[Poxviridae|pox viruses]] belong to this family.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moss|first=Bernard|year=2013|title=Poxvirus DNA Replication|journal=Cold Spring Harbor Perspectives in Biology|volume=5|issue=9|doi=10.1101/cshperspect.a010199|issn=1943-0264|pmc=3753712|pmid=23838441|page=a010199}}</ref>&nbsp;\n\n==Mininucleoviridae==\n\nA new family has been proposed - [[Mininucleoviridae]] - for a family of large viruses that replicate in crustacea.<ref name=\"Subramaniam\">{{cite journal |last1=Subramaniam |first1=K |title=A New Family of DNA Viruses Causing Disease in Crustaceans from Diverse Aquatic Biomes. |journal=mBio |date=14 January 2020 |volume=11 |issue=1 |doi=10.1128/mBio.02938-19 |pmid=31937645|pmc=6960288 }}</ref> Members of this proposed family include [[Carcinus maenas virus 1]], [[Dikerogammarus haemobaphes virus 1]] and [[Panulirus argus virus 1]].\n\n==Unclassified viruses==\n\n: ''[[Cedratvirus]]''\n: ''[[Choanovirus]]''\n: ''[[Dinodnavirus]]''\n: ''[[Faustovirus]]''\n: ''[[Kaumoebavirus]]''\n: ''[[Klothovirus casanovai]]''\n: ''[[Medusavirus]]''\n: ''[[Megaklothovirus horridgei]]''\n: ''[[Meelsvirus]]''\n: ''[[Mollivirus]]''\n: ''[[Namao virus]]''\n: ''[[Orpheovirus]]''\n: ''[[Pacmanvirus]]''\n: ''[[Pandoravirus]]''\n: ''[[Platanovirus]]''\n: ''[[Tupanvirus]]''\n\n==Phylogenetics==\n\nThe ''[[Pithovirus]]'', ''[[Iridovirus]]'' and ''[[Marseillevirus]]'' appear to form a clade.<ref name=B\u00e4ckstr\u00f6m2019>{{cite journal | vauthors=B\u00e4ckstr\u00f6m D, Yutin N, J\u00f8rgensen SL, Dharamshi J, Homa F, Zaremba-Niedwiedzka K, Spang A, Wolf YI, Koonin EV, Ettema TJ |title=Virus genomes from deep sea sediments expand the ocean megavirome and support independent origins of viral gigantism |year=2019 |journal=mBio |volume=10 |issue=2 |pages=e02497-18 | doi=10.1128/mBio.02497-18 |pmid=30837339 |pmc=6401483 }}[https://mbio.asm.org/content/mbio/10/2/e02497-18.full.pdf PDF]</ref> \n\nThe origin of the NCLDVs may predate that of their eukaryotic hosts.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Guglielmini|first=Julien|last2=Woo|first2=Anthony C.|last3=Krupovic|first3=Mart|last4=Forterre|first4=Patrick|last5=Gaia|first5=Morgan|date=2019-09-10|title=Diversification of giant and large eukaryotic dsDNA viruses predated the origin of modern eukaryotes|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|language=en|volume=116|issue=39|pages=19585\u201319592|doi=10.1073/pnas.1912006116|pmid=31506349|pmc=6765235|issn=0027-8424}}</ref> \n\n==See also==\n* [[Viral eukaryogenesis]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Baltimore classification}}\n{{Virus topics}}\n\n[[Category:Nucleocytoplasmic large DNA viruses]]\n[[Category:Unaccepted virus taxa]]\n", "text_old": "{{Taxobox\n| color=violet\n| name = ''Megavirales''\n| image =\n| image_caption =\n| virus_group = i\n| subdivision_ranks = Families{{cn|date=October 2019}}\n| subdivision = \n''[[Ascoviridae]]''<br/>\n''[[Asfarviridae]]''<br/>\n''[[Iridoviridae]]''<br/>\n''[[Marseilleviridae]]''<br/>\n''[[Megaviridae]]'' (syn. ''Mimiviridae'')<br/>\n''[[Pandoraviridae]]''<br/>\n''[[Phycodnaviridae]]''<br/>\n''[[Pithoviridae]]'' <br>\n''[[Poxviridae]]''\n}}\n\nThe '''nucleocytoplasmic large DNA viruses''' '''(NCLDV)''', are a proposed order of [[DNA_virus#Group_I:_dsDNA_viruses|dsDNA]] [[virus]]es, notable for containing the '''''Megavirales''''' or [[giant virus]]es.<ref name=\"Colson2012\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Colson P, de Lamballerie X, Fournous G, Raoult D |year=2012 |title=Reclassification of giant viruses composing a fourth domain of life in the new order Megavirales|journal=Intervirology |volume=55 |issue=5 |pages=321\u2013332 |doi=10.1159/000336562 |pmid=22508375}}</ref><ref name=\"Colson2013\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Colson P, De Lamballerie X, Yutin N, Asgari S, Bigot Y, Bideshi DK, Cheng XW, Federici BA, Van Etten JL, Koonin EV, La Scola B, Raoult D |year=2013 |title=\"Megavirales\", a proposed new order for eukaryotic nucleocytoplasmic large DNA viruses |journal=Arch Virol |volume=158 |issue=12 |pages=2517\u201321 |doi=10.1007/s00705-013-1768-6 |pmid=23812617 |pmc=4066373}}</ref> There are nine families of NCLDVs that all share certain genomic and structural characteristics; however, it is uncertain whether the similarities of the different families of this group have a common viral ancestor.<ref name=\"Iyer2001\">{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1128/JVI.75.23.11720-11734.2001 | volume = 75| issue = 23| pages = 11720\u201334| date = December 2001| last1 = Iyer | first1 = L. M.| last2 = Aravind | first2 = L.| last3 = Koonin | first3 = E. V. | pmid=11689653 | pmc=114758 | title=Common Origin of Four Diverse Families of Large Eukaryotic DNA Viruses | journal = Journal of Virology }}</ref> One feature of this group is a large [[genome]] and the presence of many [[gene]]s involved in [[DNA repair]], [[DNA replication]], [[transcription (biology)|transcription]], and [[translation]]. Typically, viruses with smaller genomes do not contain genes for these processes. Most of the viruses in this family also replicate in both the host's [[cell nucleus|nucleus]] and [[cytoplasm]], thus the name nucleocytoplasmic.\n\nThere are 47 NCLDV core genes currently recognised. These include four key proteins involved in DNA replication and repair: the [[enzyme]]s [[DNA polymerase]] family B, the [[topoisomerase]] II A, the [[5-lipoxygenase-activating protein|FLAP]] [[endonuclease]] and the processing factor [[proliferating cell nuclear antigen]]. Other proteins include DNA dependent [[RNA polymerase]] II and [[transcription factor]] II B.\n\n==''Ascoviridae''==\nMembers of the family ''[[Ascoviridae]]'' come in different shapes. Some can be rod-shaped, while others are oval. They measure up to 130&nbsp;nm wide and 400&nbsp;nm long. Theses viruses have circular double stranded DNA that have a length of about 100\u2013200 kilobase pairs. They infect lepidopteran insect larvae and can infect through parasitoid wasps. Once they infect they replicate and cause death in insect pest. This allows them to control insect populations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://talk.ictvonline.org/ictv-reports/ictv_online_report/dsdna-viruses/w/ascoviridae#Citation|title=Ascoviridae\u2014Ascoviridae\u2014dsDNA Viruses\u2014International Committee on Taxonomy of Viruses (ICTV)|website=International Committee on Taxonomy of Viruses (ICTV)|language=en|access-date=2017-12-07}}</ref> Ascoviridae can have up to 180 genes in its genome. The replication of this virus takes place in the nucleus of the host cell. When it replicates, it causes the nucleus to increase in size and eventually burst. After, the virion starts to form and spread.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Asgari|first=Sassan|last2=Bideshi|first2=Dennis K|last3=Bigot|first3=Yves|last4=Federici|first4=Brian A|last5=Cheng|first5=Xiao-Wen|year=2017|title=ICTV Virus Taxonomy Profile: Ascoviridae|journal=The Journal of General Virology|volume=98|issue=1|pages=4\u20135|doi=10.1099/jgv.0.000677|issn=0022-1317|pmc=5370392|pmid=28218573}}</ref>\n\n==''Asfarviridae''==\nA member of the family ''[[Asfarviridae]]'' is a known as an asfarvirus. This virus is the cause of African swine fever. Some of the symptoms for this flu include fever, high pulse, fast breathing, and it can cause death. These symptoms can be similar to those from hog cholera, the difference is that the African swine flu can not be cured. There is no vaccine developed to fight this virus.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.britannica.com/science/African-swine-fever|title=African swine fever (ASF) {{!}} animal disease|encyclopedia=Encyclopedia Britannica|access-date=2017-12-07|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==''Iridoviridae''==\nThe ''[[Iridoviridae]]'' have linear double stranded DNA genomes up to 220 kilobases long and can code for about 211 proteins. The capsid of this virion is icosahedral shaped and can be up to 350&nbsp;nm wide. The replication cycle of this virus begins in the nucleus of the host and end in the cytoplasm. Some viruses of this family are often found infecting amphibians while other are found in insect and crustaceans.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://talk.ictvonline.org/ictv-reports/ictv_online_report/dsdna-viruses/w/iridoviridae|title=Iridoviridae\u2014Iridoviridae\u2014dsDNA Viruses\u2014International Committee on Taxonomy of Viruses (ICTV)|website=International Committee on Taxonomy of Viruses (ICTV)|language=en|access-date=2017-12-07}}</ref>\n\n==''Marseilleviridae''==\nThe ''[[Marseilleviridae]]'' viruses have double stranded DNA genomes that are about 372 kilobases long. Members of the family can have about 457 [[open reading frame]]s (ORFs) in its genome. The host organisms are [[amoeba]]e. Once it infects, viral replication takes place in the cytoplasm.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}} It was found that the genome of the family ''Marseilleviridae'' codes for about 28 different proteins.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Boyer|first=Micka\u00ebl|last2=Yutin|first2=Natalya|last3=Pagnier|first3=Isabelle|last4=Barrassi|first4=Lina|last5=Fournous|first5=Ghislain|last6=Espinosa|first6=Leon|last7=Robert|first7=Catherine|last8=Azza|first8=Sa\u00efd|last9=Sun|first9=Siyang|date=2009-12-22|title=Giant Marseillevirus highlights the role of amoebae as a melting pot in emergence of chimeric microorganisms|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America|volume=106|issue=51|pages=21848\u201321853|doi=10.1073/pnas.0911354106|issn=0027-8424|pmc=2799887|pmid=20007369|bibcode=2009PNAS..10621848B}}</ref>&nbsp;The capsid of the marseillevirus is about 250&nbsp;nm wide with a geometry shape of an icosahedral. The replication of this virus usually occurs near the nucleus once it infects the amoeba. Once the virus infects it can cause a shape change in the host\u2019s nucleus.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2014-10-01|title=The expanding family Marseilleviridae|journal=Virology|volume=466\u2013467|pages=27\u201337|doi=10.1016/j.virol.2014.07.014|pmid=25104553|issn=0042-6822 | last1 = Aherfi | first1 = Sarah}}</ref>\n\n==''Megaviridae''==\nThe ''[[Megaviridae]]'' contains some of the largest viruses ever discovered. They have linear double stranded DNA genomes with the length of 1,259,197 base pairs, which is larger than some small bacteria. Within in this genome 1,100 proteins are coded. 74.76% of the base pairs are represented by thymine and adenine. The ''Megaviridae'' virus can be found infecting acanthamoeba or other protozoan clades. &nbsp;Once the virus infects the host, the replication cycle takes place in the cytoplasm. Within the genome, DNA repair enzymes can be found. These are used when the DNA is harmed such as when it is exposed to ionizing radiation or UV light.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Arslan|first=Defne|last2=Legendre|first2=Matthieu|last3=Seltzer|first3=Virginie|last4=Abergel|first4=Chantal|last5=Claverie|first5=Jean-Michel|date=2011-10-18|title=Distant Mimivirus relative with a larger genome highlights the fundamental features of Megaviridae|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|language=en|volume=108|issue=42|pages=17486\u201317491|doi=10.1073/pnas.1110889108|issn=0027-8424|pmid=21987820|pmc=3198346|bibcode=2011PNAS..10817486A}}</ref>\n\nTraditionally these viruses have been grouped into a family ''Mimiviridae''. Later it appeared that the viruses of the ''Organic Lake Phycodna Group'' (OLPG) are more related to Mimiviruses than to [[Phycodnaviridae|Phycodnaviruses]]. For this reason it has been proposed adding them to legacy Mimiviridae as new subfamily ''Mesomimivirinae'' in order to form the more comprehensive family ''Megaviridae''. However, the term ''Mimiviridae'' nowadays is used ''sensu lato'' synonymous with ''Megaviridae''.<ref name=Schulz2017>{{Cite journal|last=Schulz|first=Frederik|last2=Yutin|first2=Natalya|last3=Ivanova|first3=Natalia N.|last4=Ortega|first4=Davi R.|last5=Lee|first5=Tae Kwon|last6=Vierheilig|first6=Julia|last7=Daims|first7=Holger|last8=Horn|first8=Matthias|last9=Wagner|first9=Michael|date=2017-04-07|title=Giant viruses with an expanded complement of translation system components|journal=Science|language=en|volume=356|issue=6333|pages=82\u201385|doi=10.1126/science.aal4657|pmid=28386012|issn=0036-8075|bibcode=2017Sci...356...82S|url=https://cloudfront.escholarship.org/dist/prd/content/qt0kf9t6gn/qt0kf9t6gn.pdf}}, UCPMS ID: 1889607, [http://escholarship.org/uc/item/0kf9t6gn.pdf PDF]</ref><ref>Eugene V Koonin, Mart Krupovic, Natalya Yutin: [https://www.researchgate.net/publication/272946690_Evolution_of_double-stranded_DNA_viruses_of_eukaryotes_From_bacteriophages_to_transposons_to_giant_viruses Evolution of double-stranded DNA viruses of eukaryotes: From bacteriophages to transposons to giant viruses], in: ResearchGate Literature Review February 2015, [[doi: 10.1111/nyas.12728]], Figure 3</ref><ref>Natalya Yutin et al.: [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3620924/ Mimiviridae: clusters of orthologous genes, reconstruction of gene repertoire evolution and proposed expansion of the giant virus family], in: Virol J. 2013; 10: 106, [[doi: 10.1186/1743-422X-10-106]]</ref><ref>Blog of Carolina Reyes, Kenneth Stedman: [https://www.researchgate.net/post/Are_Phaeocystis_globosa_viruses_OLPG_and_Organic_Lake_phycodnavirus_a_part_of_the_Phycodnaviridae_or_Mimiviridae Are Phaeocystis globosa viruses (OLPG) and Organic Lake phycodnavirus a part of the Phycodnaviridae or Mimiviridae?], on ResearchGate, Jan. 8, 2016</ref><ref>Fumito Maruyama and Shoko Ueki: [http://journal.frontiersin.org/article/10.3389/fmicb.2016.01942/full Evolution and Phylogeny of Large DNA Viruses, ''Mimiviridae'' and ''Phycodnaviridae'' Including Newly Characterized ''Heterosigma akashiwo Virus''], in: Front. Microbiol., 30 November 2016, [[doi: 10.3389/fmicb.2016.01942]]</ref><ref name=\"WZhang\">Weijia Zhang et al.:  [https://www.nature.com/articles/srep15131 Four novel algal virus genomes discovered from Yellowstone Lake metagenomes], in: Scientific Reports 5, Article number: 15131 (2015), especially Figure 6, [[doi: 10.1038/srep15131]]</ref> \n\n==''Pandoraviridae''==\n''[[Pandoravirus|Pandoraviridae]]'' Discovered in 2013 from a coastal water sample in Chile. It is mostly found infecting amoebae. It has a length of 1 micrometer long and .5 micrometer wide. Its genome can be up to 2.5 million base pairs long.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Yong|first=Ed|title=Giant viruses open Pandora's box|url=https://www.nature.com/news/giant-viruses-open-pandora-s-box-1.13410|journal=Nature|language=en|doi=10.1038/nature.2013.13410|year=2013}}</ref> The replication of this virus take place in the cytoplasm. Like other giant viruses, it affect the host\u2019s nucleus and can take up to 15 hours to start infecting.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Aherfi|first=Sarah|last2=Colson|first2=Philippe|last3=La Scola|first3=Bernard|last4=Raoult|first4=Didier|date=2016-03-22|title=Giant Viruses of Amoebas: An Update|journal=Frontiers in Microbiology|volume=7|pages=349|doi=10.3389/fmicb.2016.00349|issn=1664-302X|pmc=4801854|pmid=27047465}}</ref> Although it is found in water, it does not affect humans, it may actually help us by increasing the production of oxygen in aquatic environments.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2013/07/130718-viruses-pandoraviruses-science-biology-evolution/|title=Biggest Virus Yet Found, May Be Fourth Domain of Life?|date=2013-07-19|access-date=2017-12-07}}</ref>'''&nbsp;'''\n\n==''Phycodnaviridae''==\nThe ''[[Phycodnaviridae]]'' are icosahedral in shape with a double-stranded DNA molecule. Some members of this family can have a linear double stranded DNA while others have a circular double stranded DNA. The genome has been found to be up to 560 kilobases in length. Up to 50% of the DNA can be represented by guanine or cytosine. This virus is known to infect algae, which means it is found in the ocean.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Wilson|first=W. H.|last2=Van Etten|first2=J. L.|last3=Allen|first3=M. J.|date=2009|title=The Phycodnaviridae: The Story of How Tiny Giants Rule the World|volume=328|pages=1\u201342|issn=0070-217X|pmc=2908299|pmid=19216434|doi=10.1007/978-3-540-68618-7_1|series=Current Topics in Microbiology and Immunology|isbn=978-3-540-68617-0}}</ref>\n\n==''Pithoviridae''==\nThe ''[[Pithovirus|Pithoviridae]]'' have only two known representatives. These viruses infects amoebas and can survive in low temperatures. For years this virus was believed to be frozen, but due to climate change it has begun to show up again.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sciencenewsforstudents.org/article/return-giant-zombie-virus|title=Return of the giant zombie virus|last=Ornes|first=Stephen|date=2017-07-31|work=Science News for Students|access-date=2017-12-07|language=en}}</ref>&nbsp;This is a double stranded DNA virus with its size being 610 kilobases long. The genome is estimated to code for 476 open reading frames. The viron is rod shaped with a length of 1,100&nbsp;nm long and 500&nbsp;nm in diameter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://viralzone.expasy.org/4237?outline=all_by_species|title=Pithovirus|website=viralzone.expasy.org|access-date=2017-12-07}}</ref>\n\n==''Poxviridae''==\nThe ''[[Poxviridae]]'' have a linear double-stranded DNA molecule that can have a length of up to 230 kilobases. The replication of these viruses takes place in the cytoplasm. [[Smallpox]], [[cowpox]], and other [[Poxviridae|pox viruses]] belong to this family.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moss|first=Bernard|year=2013|title=Poxvirus DNA Replication|journal=Cold Spring Harbor Perspectives in Biology|volume=5|issue=9|doi=10.1101/cshperspect.a010199|issn=1943-0264|pmc=3753712|pmid=23838441|page=a010199}}</ref>&nbsp;\n\n==Mininucleoviridae==\n\nA new family has been proposed - [[Mininucleoviridae]] - for a family of large viruses that replicate in crustacea.<ref name=\"Subramaniam\">{{cite journal |last1=Subramaniam |first1=K |title=A New Family of DNA Viruses Causing Disease in Crustaceans from Diverse Aquatic Biomes. |journal=mBio |date=14 January 2020 |volume=11 |issue=1 |doi=10.1128/mBio.02938-19 |pmid=31937645|pmc=6960288 }}</ref> Members of this proposed family include [[Carcinus maenas virus 1]], [[Dikerogammarus haemobaphes virus 1]] and [[Panulirus argus virus 1]].\n\n==Unclassified viruses==\n\n: ''[[Cedratvirus]]''\n: ''[[Choanovirus]]''\n: ''[[Dinodnavirus]]''\n: ''[[Faustovirus]]''\n: ''[[Kaumoebavirus]]''\n: ''[[Klothovirus casanovai]]''\n: ''[[Medusavirus]]''\n: ''[[Megaklothovirus horridgei]]''\n: ''[[Meelsvirus]]''\n: ''[[Mollivirus]]''\n: ''[[Namao virus]]''\n: ''[[Orpheovirus]]''\n: ''[[Pacmanvirus]]''\n: ''[[Pandoravirus]]''\n: ''[[Platanovirus]]''\n: ''[[Tupanvirus]]''\n\n==Phylogenetics==\n\nThe ''[[Pithovirus]]'', ''[[Iridovirus]]'' and ''[[Marseillevirus]]'' appear to form a clade.<ref name=B\u00e4ckstr\u00f6m2019>{{cite journal | vauthors=B\u00e4ckstr\u00f6m D, Yutin N, J\u00f8rgensen SL, Dharamshi J, Homa F, Zaremba-Niedwiedzka K, Spang A, Wolf YI, Koonin EV, Ettema TJ |title=Virus genomes from deep sea sediments expand the ocean megavirome and support independent origins of viral gigantism |year=2019 |journal=mBio |volume=10 |issue=2 |pages=e02497-18 | doi=10.1128/mBio.02497-18 |pmid=30837339 |pmc=6401483 }}[https://mbio.asm.org/content/mbio/10/2/e02497-18.full.pdf PDF]</ref> \n\nThe origin of the NCLDVs may predate that of their eukaryotic hosts.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Guglielmini|first=Julien|last2=Woo|first2=Anthony C.|last3=Krupovic|first3=Mart|last4=Forterre|first4=Patrick|last5=Gaia|first5=Morgan|date=2019-09-10|title=Diversification of giant and large eukaryotic dsDNA viruses predated the origin of modern eukaryotes|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|language=en|volume=116|issue=39|pages=19585\u201319592|doi=10.1073/pnas.1912006116|pmid=31506349|pmc=6765235|issn=0027-8424}}</ref> \n\n==See also==\n* [[Viral eukaryogenesis]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Baltimore classification}}\n{{Virus topics}}\n\n[[Category:Nucleocytoplasmic large DNA viruses]]\n[[Category:Unaccepted virus taxa]]\n", "name_user": "SDC", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nucleocytoplasmic_large_DNA_viruses"}
{"title_page": "Kalvin Phillips", "text_new": "{{short description|English footballer}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Kalvin Phillips\n| image = Kalvin_Phillips_Leeds_United.jpg\n| image_size = 200\n| caption = Phillips playing for [[Leeds United]] in 2015\n| fullname = Kalvin Mark Phillips<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.efl.com/siteassets/image/201920/general-news/efl-squad-numbering-06.09.2019.pdf |title=Notification of shirt numbers: Leeds United |publisher=English Football League |page=36 |accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1995|12|2|df=y}}<ref name=\"11v11\">{{cite web |url=https://www.11v11.com/players/kalvin-phillips-248796/ |title=Kalvin Phillips |website=11v11.com |publisher=AFS Enterprises |accessdate=6 May 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Leeds]], England\n| height = {{convert|1.77|m|order=flip}}<ref name=\"11v11\"/>\n| currentclub = [[Leeds United|Leeds United]]\n| clubnumber = 23\n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 = 2003\u20132010\n| youthclubs1 = Wortley Juniors\n| youthyears2 = 2010\u20132014\n| youthclubs2 = [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]]\n| years1 = 2014\u2013\n| clubs1 = [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]]\n| caps1 = 157\n| goals1 = 11\n| club-update = 15 February 2020 (UTC)\n}}\n'''Kalvin Mark Phillips''' (born 2 December 1995) is an English professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays for [[Leeds United]] as a [[Midfielder#Central midfielder|central midfielder]]. He plays mainly as a [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|defensive midfielder]] and can also play as a [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|centre back]].<ref name=\"2015offer\"/> He is the greatest footballer ever and much better than any Chelsea player.\n\n==Club career==\nAfter progressing through [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]]'s youth ranks, Leeds-born Phillips signed his first professional deal with the club in the summer of 2014, retaining him for the 2014\u201315 season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.leedsunited.com/news/team-news/2418/united-youngsters-sign-up |title=United youngsters sign up |publisher=Leeds United F.C. |date=9 July 2014 |accessdate=20 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/leeds-united-rising-star-to-commit-to-whites-1-7289683 |title=Leeds United: Rising star to commit to Whites |newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post |date=3 June 2015 |accessdate=20 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2014\u201315 season===\nDuring the 2014\u201315 season, Phillips became the captain of the Development Squad and Under 18's team. Phillips joined the first team for the trip to [[Sunderland A.F.C|Sunderland]] in the [[FA Cup]] third round on 4 January 2015; he was unused substitute in a 1\u20130 defeat. On 30 March 2015, Leeds Academy coach [[Jason Blunt]] revealed that he felt the form of Phillips for the Under 18's and Development Squad would see Phillips become a future first team fans favourite.<ref>{{cite web | url =http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/leeds-united/latest-whites-news/leeds-united-phillips-can-become-a-real-fans-favourite-1-7182469  | title = Leeds United: Phillips can become a real fans' favourite | website = Yorkshire Evening Post | date = 30 March 2015| accessdate = 30 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nPhillips made further appearances on the bench for the first team in league games over the following months before making his professional debut against [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] in 4\u20133 defeat on 6 April 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=Wolverhampton Wanderers v Leeds United|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/32111079|publisher=BBC Sport|date=6 April 2015}}</ref> Along with [[Sam Byram]], [[Charlie Taylor (footballer, born 1993)|Charlie Taylor]], [[Alex Mowatt]] and [[Lewis Cook (footballer, born 1997)|Lewis Cook]]; Phillips was the latest graduate of a promising group of Academy players to regularly feature under former youth boss [[Neil Redfearn]] in the [[2014\u201315 in English football|2014\u201315]] campaign.\n\nOn 11 April 2015, Phillips retained his position in the Leeds starting 11, making his home debut against [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] at [[Elland Road]]. Phillips marked the game with his first senior goal in only his second appearance, although the match finished in a 2\u20131 defeat to Cardiff.<ref>{{cite web | url =http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/leeds-united/latest-whites-news/leeds-united-1-cardiff-city-2-phillips-goal-a-rare-highlight-in-defeat-1-7205759  | title = Leeds United 1 Cardiff City 2: Phillips goal a rare highlight in defeat | website = Yorkshire Evening Post | date = 12 April 2015 | accessdate = 12 April 2015}}</ref> At the end of the season, he was offered and accepted a new two-year contract.<ref name=2015offer/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/33021402 |title=Kalvin Philips: Leeds United midfielder signs new deal |publisher=BBC Sport |date=5 June 2015 |accessdate=20 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2015\u201316 season===\n\nOn 31 July 2015, Phillips was given the number 27 shirt for the upcoming 2015\u201316 season.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Leeds United F.C. | date= 31 July 2015 | accessdate= 31 July 2015 | title= 2015/16 squad numbers announced | url=http://www.leedsunited.com/news/article/13qz1j2snco7s1ip1xc6j5mk2b/title/201516-squad-numbers-announced}}</ref> However, with Redfearn replaced as head coach during the summer, Phillips played just 10 league games over the course of the season under head coaches [[Uwe Rosler]] and then [[Steve Evans (footballer, born 1962)|Steve Evans]].\n\n===2016\u201317 season===\n\nIn June 2016, only days after the appointment of new head coach [[Garry Monk]], highly rated Phillips was offered a new 3-year contract at Leeds.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Leeds United F.C. | date= 17 June 2016 | accessdate= 17 June 2016 | title= Leeds United: Phillips commits future to Whites | url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/leeds-united-phillips-commits-future-to-whites-1-7970057}}</ref> On 23 June, Phillips signed the new 3-year contract extension to stay at the club until the summer of 2019.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Leeds United F.C. | date= 23 June 2016 | accessdate= 23 June 2016 | title= Kalvin commits future to United | url=http://www.leedsunited.com/news/article/13grzz3o3o0x81pumvnl5addbg/title/kalvin-commits-future-to-united}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 August 2016, Phillips scored his first goal of the 2016\u201317 season, with a stunning long range free kick against [[Nottingham Forest]] in a 3\u20131 defeat.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/37138714|title=Nottingham Forest 3 Leeds United 1|publisher=BBC Sport|date=27 August 2016 |accessdate=20 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter an injury to captain [[Liam Bridcutt]] in September 2016,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.express.co.uk/sport/football/716076/Liam-Bridcutt-Garry-Monk-Leeds-United-Injury-News-Rumours-Gossip |title=Garry Monk delivers devastating injury update on Leeds star: Could be out for two months |work=Express  |publisher=  |date=30 September 2016 |accessdate=30 September 2016}}</ref> Phillips alongside [[Eunan O'Kane]] or [[Ronaldo Vieira (footballer, born 1998)|Ronaldo Vieira]] established himself as an important player at the heart of Leeds' central midfield.\n\nPhillips' impressive form for Leeds saw him win the [[EFL Championship]] Young Player Of The Month Award for October 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.leedsunited.com/news/team-news/21357/efl-kalvin-phillips-named-young-player-of-the-month |title=EFL: Kalvin Phillips named Young Player of the Month |publisher=Leeds United F.C. |date=21 November 2016 |accessdate=21 November 2016}}</ref> On 9 December 2016, Phillips was given his first professional red card after giving away a penalty in a 2\u20130 defeat against then league leaders [[Brighton & Hove Albion]] by turning away a goal-bound shot with his arm, the penalty was converted by [[Glenn Murray]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.skysports.com/watch/video/sports/football/10689813/phillips-hands-brighton-the-lead|title=Phillips hands Brighton the lead |publisher=Sky Sports |date=9 December 2016 |accessdate=9 December 2016}}</ref> On 7 March 2017, Phillips received his 2nd red card of the season in a 1\u20131 draw against Fulham.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/leeds-united-phillips-gets-two-match-ban-from-fa-after-picking-up-third-red-card-of-the-season-1-8427640 |title=Phillips gets two-match ban from FA after picking up third red card of the season |newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post |date=8 March 2017 |accessdate=8 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2017\u201318 season===\n\nOn 6 August 2017, the opening day of the 2017\u201318 Championship season, Phillips scored a brace to ensure Leeds beat [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] 3\u20132.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.leedsunited.com/news/team-news/22152/report-bolton-wanderers-2-3-leeds-united |title=Report: Bolton Wanderers 2\u20133 Leeds United |publisher=Leeds United F.C. |date= 6 August 2017 |accessdate=6 August 2017}}</ref> On 9 September he scored his third goal of the season in the match against [[Burton Albion]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41132801 | title=Leeds Vs Burton Albion |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=9 September 2017}}</ref> His fifth of the season, came on 27 October 2017 in a 1\u20132 defeat in the Yorkshire Derby against [[Sheffield United]].\n\nHe started the season partnering O'Kane in the heart of Leeds' midfield, however after a good start to the season, Leeds suffered a lack of form prior to the sacking of head coach [[Thomas Christiansen]] in February 2018,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42940326|title=Leeds dismiss manager Thomas Christiansen after eight months|publisher=BBC Sport|date=4 February 2018|accessdate=4 February 2018}}</ref> with Phillips and O'Kane finding little spells in and out the side with Vieira given more opportunities and the arrival of January 2018 signing [[Adam Forshaw]].<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post|date=18 January 2018|accessdate=18 January 2018|author=Lee Sobot|url=https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/done-deal-adam-forshaw-joins-leeds-united-in-4-5m-deal-from-middlesbrough-1-8966950|title=Done Deal: Adam Forshaw joins Leeds United in \u00a34.5m deal from Middlesbrough}}</ref>\n\nHe ended the season with 7 goals and 3 assists, which represented his best scoring season of his career so far.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/teams/leeds-united/top-scorers|title=Leeds United Top Scorers|website=BBC Sport|access-date=17 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2018\u201319 season===\nOn 19 July 2018, Phillips revealed he had been training as a [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|centre back]] and a [[Midfielder#Deep-lying playmaker|deep-lying playmaker]] ahead of the 2018\u201319 season, as part of new Head Coach [[Marcelo Bielsa]]'s tactics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.leeds-live.co.uk/sport/leeds-united/kalvin-phillips-centre-back-leeds-14923176|title=Kalvin Phillips on how Marcelo Bielsa has been training him as a centre-back this summer|website=Leeds Live|access-date=19 July 2018}}</ref> As the season started, he was deployed as the holding midfielder in a 4\u20131\u20134\u20131 formation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/leeds-united-midfielder-phillips-is-lynchpin-of-the-bielsa-revolution-1-9306238|title=Leeds United: Midfielder Phillips is lynchpin of the Bielsa revolution|access-date=22 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 August, he made his 100th senior appearance for Leeds in a 2\u20132 draw against [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/full-time-swansea-city-2-leeds-united-2-hernandez-back-to-haunt-swans-as-whites-go-top-1-9312620|title=FULL TIME: Swansea City 2 Leeds United 2: Hernandez back to haunt Swans as Whites go top|access-date=22 August 2018}}</ref> Phillips was utilised as a  deep-lying [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|defensive midfielder]] for Leeds under Bielsa, Phillps also would play as a centre back if Leeds' lined up in a 3-man defence.<ref name=2015offer>{{cite news |url=https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/bielsa-highlights-centre-back-options-at-leeds-united-but-would-welcome-one-more-1-9284284 |title=Bielsa highlights centre-back options at Leeds United but would welcome one more |newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post |date=4 August 2018 |accessdate=16 November 2018}}</ref> In October 2018, his impressive form in his new position's under Bielsa's management,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.teamtalk.com/news/exclusive-arsenal-everton-among-12-prem-sides-scouting-leeds-ace|title=EXCLUSIVE: Arsenal, Everton among 12 Prem sides scouting Leeds ace|access-date=16 November 2018}}</ref> saw Phillips briefly linked with a possible call up to [[Gareth Southgate]]'s [[England national football team|England national team]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/kalvin-phillips-for-england-mason-mount-s-call-up-shows-the-championship-is-on-gareth-southgate-s-radar-1-9392468|title=Kalvin Phillips for England? Mason Mount's call-up shows the Championship is on Gareth Southgate's radar|access-date=16 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.leeds-live.co.uk/sport/leeds-united/england-croatia-leeds-kalvin-phillips-15269967|title=Kalvin Phillips on his England dream after Gareth Southgate calls up Mason Mount|access-date=16 November 2018}}</ref> After a knee injury to Captain [[Liam Cooper]] on 1 December 2018 in a 1\u20130 win against [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Injury Update: Liam Cooper & Stuart Dallas |url=https://www.leedsunited.com/news/team-news/24214/injury-update-liam-cooper-stuart-dallas |newspaper=Yorkshire Post |date=5 December 2018 |accessdate=7 December 2018}}</ref> Phillips deputised several games playing as an outright centre back until Coopers return in mid-January.<ref>{{cite news |title=KALVIN PHILLIPS DELIVERS HONEST VERDICT ON PLAYING CENTRE-BACK FOR LEEDS UNITED |url=https://footballleagueworld.co.uk/kalvin-phillips-delivers-honest-verdict-on-playing-centre-back-for-leeds-united/ |publisher=Football League World|date=8 April 2018 |accessdate=19 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter returning to his defensive midfielder position, he scored his first goal of the season in Leeds' 1\u20131 draw against [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] on 9 February 2019, with Phillips scoring the equaliser in the 11th minute of injury time.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/feb/09/middlesbrough-leeds-united-championship-match-report |title=Leeds' Kalvin Phillips rescues point at Boro after Clarke taken to hospital|publisher=The Guardian|date=9 February 2019 |accessdate=19 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019 he was selected to the [[2018\u201319 EFL Championship|EFL 2018\u201319 Championship Team of the Season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47710254|title=EFL awards: Che Adams, Teemu Pukki & Billy Sharp on Championship shortlist|date=26 March 2019|accessdate=28 March 2019|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 4 May 2019, Phillips was named the [[Yorkshire Evening Post]] Player of the Year for the 2018/19 season.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/leeds-united-latest/from-kalvin-phillips-to-rio-ferdinand-every-yep-leeds-united-player-of-the-year-since-2002-1-9749593|title=From Kalvin Phillips to Rio Ferdinand \u2013 every YEP Leeds United Player of the Year since 2002|date=4 May 2019|accessdate=15 May 2019|publisher=YEP}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2018\u201319 Leeds United F.C. season]], Phillips played 46 games in all competitions, scoring 1 goal, after Leeds finished the regular season in third place after dropping out of the automatic promotion places with 3 games left after a defeat to 10 man [[Wigan Athletic]] on 19 April,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47904094 |title=Leeds 1 Wigan 2|date=19 April 2019 |publisher=BBC Sport | accessdate=15 May 2019}}</ref> Leeds qualified for the playoffs, Phillips started the playoffs fixtures versus sixth-placed [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]], despite Leeds taking a 1\u20130 win at Pride Park into the home leg at Elland Road, Leeds lost 2\u20134 in the 2nd leg, with Leeds down to 10 men after the red card of [[Gaetano Berardi]],<ref name=\"BBC Sport\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48196167|title=Leeds United 2\u20134 Derby County (Derby win 4\u20133 on agg)|publisher=BBC Sport|date=15 May 2019}}</ref> and saw Derby progress to the final against [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] 3\u20134 on aggregate.<ref name=\"BBC Sport\"/>\n\n===2019\u201320 season===\nIn July 2019, after being linked with a move to newly promoted [[Premier League]] side [[Aston Villa]], with Leeds putting a \u00a330 million transfer valuation on Phillips,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.teamtalk.com/news/leeds-slap-huge-30m-asking-price-on-star-man-amid-villa-links|title=Leeds slap huge \u00a330m asking price on star man amid Villa links|date=30 June 2019|website=TeamTalk}}</ref> Leeds opened contract talks with Phillips over a new contract.<ref name=\"JOE URQUHART\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/leeds-united-latest/leeds-united-open-contract-talks-with-midfielder-kalvin-phillips-1-9861251 |title=Leeds United open contract talks with midfielder Kalvin Phillips|date=8 July 2019 |work=Yorkshire Evening Post | author=Joe Urquhart | accessdate=8 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49014922|title=Kalvin Phillips: Leeds United in talks with midfielder over new deal|date=17 July 2019|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 8 August 2019, it was revealed that Leeds had rejected bids for Phillips during the 2019 transfer window in order to keep him at the club,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/leeds-united-latest/angus-kinnear-interview-part-two-leeds-united-rejected-35m-worth-of-bids-strengthened-and-addressed-financial-fair-play-requirements-1-9924953|title=Angus Kinnear interview \u2013 part two: Leeds United rejected \u00a335m worth of bids, strengthened and addressed Financial Fair Play requirements|work=Yorkshire Evening Post|date=8 August 2019}}</ref> with bids for Phillips rejected around the \u00a327 million pound mark.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theathletic.co.uk/1093748/2019/08/27/kalvin-phillips-is-leeds-next-homegrown-gem-yet-his-school-tried-to-warn-him-off-football/|title=Kalvin Phillips is Leeds' next homegrown gem yet his school tried to warn him off football|date=26 August 2019|via=The Athletic}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, he signed a new 5-year contract with Leeds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49636362|title=Kalvin Phillips: Leeds United midfielder signs new contract|date=9 September 2019|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> On Leeds United's centenary week, Phillips scored the winning goal against [[Birmingham City]], with the game finishing 1\u20130 which took place in front of another large crowd at Elland Road.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/leeds-vs-birmham/report/409486|title=Leeds 1\u20130 Birmingham: Kalvin Phillips hits United winner at Elland Road|date=19 October 2019|via=www.skysports.com}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, Phillips' Leeds form in [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|defensive midfield]] under [[Marcelo Bielsa]] saw calls for him to be called up to the [[England national football team|England national team]] squad.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11689/11870151/kalvin-phillips-interview-the-best-defensive-midfielder-in-england|title=Kalvin Phillips interview: The best defensive midfielder in England?|date=26 November 2019|via=www.skysports.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.teamtalk.com/news/pundit-explains-why-leeds-star-is-better-england-pick-than-rice-winks|title=Kalvin Phillips interview: The best defensive midfielder in England?Leeds star is better England pick than Rice, Winks, claims pundit|date=21 November 2019|via=Talksport}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/latest-leeds-united-news/picture-facing-leeds-united-star-kalvin-phillips-if-gareth-southgate-grant-midfielder-england-call-1304160|title=The picture facing Leeds United star Kalvin Phillips if Gareth Southgate is to grant midfielder an England call|date=20 November 2019|via=Yorkshire Evening Post}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/5liveSport/status/1196523002625576961|title=Could #LUFC's Kalvin Phillips be an option for Gareth Southgate's #ThreeLions at #EURO2020?|date=15 November 2019|via=BBC Five Live Twitter Page}}</ref> On 6 January 2020, Phillips was heavily praised for his performance against [[Premier League]] side [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in a 1-0 defeat in the [[FA Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/leeds-uniteds-kalvin-phillips-passed-arsenal-premier-league-test-now-its-sheffield-wednesday-wizard-barry-bannan-1360807|title=Leeds United's Kalvin Phillips passed Arsenal Premier League test, now it's Sheffield Wednesday wizard Barry Bannan|date=10 January 2020|via=Yorkshire Evening Post}}</ref> England manager [[Gareth Southgate]] watched Phillips in January 2020 ahead of a possible call up.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theathletic.co.uk/1532978/2020/01/16/leeds-kalvin-phillips-ready-for-england/|title=He\u2019s playing in the Championship and developed outside \u2018the system\u2019 but Kalvin Phillips is ready for England|date=15 January 2020|via=The Athletic}}</ref> On 18 January, Phillips was sent off against [[Q.P.R.]] in a 1-0 defeat.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/leeds-uniteds-kalvin-phillips-apologises-fans-qpr-red-card-and-vows-help-make-promotion-dream-come-true-1369389|title=Leeds United's Kalvin Phillips apologises to fans for QPR red card and vows to help make promotion dream come true|date=26 January 2020|via=Yorkshire Evening Post}}</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\nAfter starting his career as a [[Midfielder#Box-to-box midfielder|box-to-box]] [[Midfielder#Central midfielder|central midfielder]], before the start of the 2018/19 season Phillips was converted into a [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|defensive midfielder]] by [[Marcelo Bielsa]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.leeds-live.co.uk/sport/leeds-united/kalvin-phillips-marcelo-bielsa-leeds-15508583|title=The evolution of Kalvin Phillips under Marcelo Bielsa \u2013 in their own words|date=6 December 2018|accessdate=2 July 2019|publisher=Leeds Live}}</ref> He is known for his range of short sharp passing, long ball distribution and ability to start attacks whilst covering his defensive duties, with him described as a 'linchpin'.<ref name=\"JOE URQUHART\"/>\n\nMarcelo Bielsa described his style \"He's very good at getting the ball and putting it into another space, a better space. He's very good when he has to cover the team when our full-backs go in attack. And when we are outnumbered, he is very good with his defending.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/leeds-united-latest/leeds-united-midfielder-phillips-is-lynchpin-of-the-bielsa-revolution-1-9306238|title=Leeds United: Midfielder Phillips is lynchpin of the Bielsa revolution|date=17 August 2018|accessdate=2 July 2019|newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post}}</ref> Phillips was also converted into playing as a [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|centre back]] under Bielsa.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/leeds-united-latest/kalvin-phillips-can-add-a-new-dimension-to-leeds-united-s-defence-1-9278531|title=Kalvin Phillips can add a new dimension to Leeds United's defence|date=1 August 2018|accessdate=2 July 2019|newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/leeds-united-latest/pontus-jansson-picture-puts-leeds-united-centre-back-situation-back-under-microscope-1-9864863 |title=Pontus Jansson picture puts Leeds United centre-back situation back under microscope|date=8 July 2019 |newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post | author= Lee Sobot | accessdate=8 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nFor his similar style of play, Phillips was given the nickname \"Yorkshire Pirlo\" by Leeds fans in homage to the former [[Midfielder#Deep-lying playmaker|deep-lying playmaker]] [[Andrea Pirlo]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://footballleagueworld.co.uk/the-yorkshire-pirlo-key-midfielders-contribution-leaves-these-leeds-fans-delighted/ |title=Leeds United 'The Yorkshire Pirlo' \u2013 key midfielder's controbution leaves these Leeds fans delighted |date=9 February 2019 |work= Football League World | accessdate=2 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/leeds-united-latest/leeds-united-midfielder-phillips-is-lynchpin-of-the-bielsa-revolution-1-9306238|title=From Kalvin Phillips to Rio Ferdinand \u2013 every YEP Leeds United Player of the Year since 2002|date=4 May 2019|accessdate=15 May 2019|newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{updated|match played 15 February 2020}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Club\n!r